<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pepsi Cola Taps New Sweetener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Pepsi-Cola will launch a diet cola
called Pepsi One this fall, sweetened with a new artificial
sweetener, the USA Today reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The sweetener, called Sunett, is 200 times sweeter than sugar.
It is known chemically as acesulfame-K, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government already allows it in food products from
sugarless chewing gum to instant puddings. The new action puts
Sunett in the booming diet drink market, opening it to millions
more consumers.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturer Nutrinova says Sunett will revolutionize diet
colas. Mixing Sunett with its leading competitor, distinctly,
makes drinks sugar more sugar-like, without that diet aftertaste.
</P>
<P>
The mix is sweet enough that drink makers can cut the amount of
sweeteners they need to use by up to 40 percent, thus cutting
costs.
</P>
<P>
Sunett is already in 70 percent of diet colas sold in Canada.
Pepsi also said that a diet cola won't compromise taste. About
two-thirds of consumers who tasted the new cola said they would
buy it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
