<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Takes Steep Drop in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. construction spending
fell 1.5 percent in May, the first drop in six months and the
largest in more than four years, the Commerce Department reported
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The decline to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 633.5
billion U.S. dollars followed five consecutive gains, according to
the department. It was the sharpest drop since January 1994.
</P>
<P>
Until May, construction spending had been supported by low U.S.
interest rates, produced as a side effect of Asia's financial
crises, and also by fierce competition among banks eager to
finance real estate development.
</P>
<P>
The decrease in May was led by government construction, which
declined 4 percent to an annual rate of 140.2 billion dollars.
Spending increased slightly on hospitals and held steady for
schools. But it fell for highways and streets, sewer systems,
water-supply facilities and other public buildings such as
offices, prisons, police and fire stations and courthouses.
</P>
<P>
The construction spending also fell for commercial projects,
down 1.7 percent to an annual rate of 165.3 billion dollars.
Declines in spending on factories, offices and hotels offset an
increase at shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
Residential construction dipped 0.7 percent to an annual rate
of 286.6 billion dollars. Remodeling spending increased slightly,
but spending fell on construction of single-family homes and
apartments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
