<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heat wave Hits Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A heat wave is on Wednesday hitting
Greece with temperatures in many parts of the country soaring to
39 degrees and state services are remaining on alert to deal with
any problems stemming from the hot weather.
</P>
<P>
In the capital of Athens, emergency calls for ambulances on
Wednesday increased 20 percent compared to Tuesday, and most of
the calls requested assistance for people suffering from heart and
respiratory problems.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Athens, with the mercury hitting 37 degrees, came
to a standstill for several hours from power cuts reportedly
caused by high electricity consumption.
</P>
<P>
The heat wave, which began several days ago and will last four
days with temperatures to rise to 42 degrees at the weekend, has
been caused by an inflow of hot air from northern Africa and
special atmospheric conditions over Greece which have forced the
hot air down, the National Meteorological Service (EMY) warned.
</P>
<P>
The highest temperature was recorded on July 10, 1977, with
thermometers hitting 48 degrees centigrade in Athens, and the
longest heat wave lasted from July 19 to July 27, 1987, leading to
the deaths of hundreds of people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
