<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Discusses 2000 Computer Snag </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Finance Minister Herbert
Murerwa Wednesday said a co-ordinated approach is needed to
resolve the problem which will be caused by computers by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
"The year 2000 problem has to be approached as a major project
within any organization," the minister told a Reserve Bank of
Zimbabwe workshop organized to address the problem, the Zimbabwe
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Both from the finance and manpower point of view, the problem
is enormous for individual organizations to tackle on their own.
A unified approach is the only way forward," he said.
</P>
<P>
The year 2000 posed a major challenge for financial
institutions, government departments and business organizations
as many automated applications would cease to function normally
because of the way date fields had been handled in the past, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Early computer programs stored the last digits of the year as
they tried to minimize the amount of storage and the cost of
memory.
</P>
<P>
At the turn of the century, computers would treat the year
2000 as 1900, resulting in ambiguity and miscalculations. This
might cause many computer applications to behave unpredictably or
fail completely.
</P>
<P>
Murerwa said failure to address this issue in time would
result in operational problems or bankruptcy, and could disrupt
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
"We must take the necessary steps to ensure such problems are
minimized," he said.
</P>
<P>
Worldwide estimates for solving the problem were being put at
between 300 billion and 600 billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the Reserve Bank, Leonard Tsumba, told the workshop
that the Central Bank, in conjunction with the Bankers
Association, had embarked on a comprehensive awareness campaign
to ensure all business organizations and the government would take
appropriate measures to upgrade their computer systems to become
compliant.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank had started working with the Swiss-based Bank for
International Settlements to ensure global information network
would not fail after December 1999, Tsumba said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
