<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Ireland Assembly Holds First Meeting in Belfast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The 108 newly-elected members of the
Northern Ireland Assembly held their inaugural meeting on
Wednesday in Belfast, marking a milestone in the long peace
process in the province.
</P>
<P>
Lord John Alderdice, the government-appointed assembly speaker,
chaired the first meeting. The assembly is one of the main
building blocks of a historic peace deal aimed at ending 30 years
of bloody conflict in the divided province.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time many arch rivals gathered in the same
room to discuss the management of Northern Irish affairs.
</P>
<P>
On the assembly's agenda will be the election of a first
minister. David Trimble, leader of the Ulster Unionists, the main
party representing Northern Ireland's pro-British Protestant
majority and the largest group in the new forum, is likely to take
the post.
</P>
<P>
The first minister will head a 12-member executive with full
legislative and executive authority in education, agriculture,
economic development, environment, finance, health and social
security.
</P>
<P>
The assembly, which gives Northern Ireland its first measure of
home-rule since 1974, will also be charged with forging closer
relations with the neighbouring Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
But the meeting is overshadowed by the coming parade of the
Protestants this weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Protestant marchers have been barred by the authority from
a Roman Catholic enclave in Drumcree, close to the strongly
pro-British town of Portadown. But they vowed on Monday to
continue their marches as planned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
