<HEADLINE> Namibia Expresses Concern over Angolan Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Namibia has expressed its
concern over the worsening security situation in Angola, Southern
African Broadcasting Association reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Namibian Defense Minister Erikki Nghimtina was quoted as
saying that his country was worried about the weekend clashes
between the government forces and the military of the National
Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), which can develop
into a full scale military conflict.
</P>
<P>
He urged Namibians in the Caprivi and Okavango region,
bordering with Angola, to refrain from crossing into their
northern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
The situation was tense in the area controlled by UNITA, a
former rebel movement which is now Angola's main opposition, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to both the Angolan government and UNITA to
refrain from military action and find a peaceful solution under
the 1994 peace accord.
</P>
<P>
President Eduardo dos Santos of Angola and UNITA leader Jonas
Savimbi signed a peace accord in Lusaka four years ago to end 20
years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
But the pact has been subjected to abuses, largely blamed on
UNITA, forcing the Security Council of the United Nations to
impose sanctions against the Angolan opposition party.  
</P>
</TEXT>
