<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Unveil New Trade Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 1 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is preparing a new
trade package embracing the whole of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) region, the Zimbabwe News Agency
report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Trade Counsellor in Zimbabwe, Hennie Erasmus
said Pretoria's blueprint is expected to be unveiled in soon.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa will classify all products into three
categories," Erasmus has told the latest issue of Commerce
Magazine published in Harare.
</P>
<P>
"The first will include all products attracting an import duty
in South Africa of up to 15 percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Products falling into this group will immediately go down to
zero for all SADC countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Estimations are that this category constitutes about 60
percent of all tariff lines in customs schedules.
</P>
<P>
The second category to be phased out over five years will
include all products attracting an import duty of more than 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
The third category will be products classified as sensitive
industries, including products in categories one and two.
</P>
<P>
Erasmus envisaged the third category to include dairy, sugar,
flour, wheat and maize.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to popular belief, Erasmus said, South Africa is
willing to open its market because imports from the region are
less than two percent of its total imports.
</P>
<P>
He said the trade talks with Zimbabwe had produced problems
for South Africa within its own business and labor sectors.
</P>
<P>
It was thought that Zimbabwe's requests for a bilateral trade
package could be better accommodated in multi-lateral talks under
SADC.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0018 </DOCNO>
