<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Govt Accords Priority to Poverty Eradication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 1 (Xinhua) -- King Birendra of Nepal said
Wednesday that human resource development and poverty eradication
by attaining a high rate of economic growth will constitute the
foremost objective of the government.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the government's annual policies and programs to
parliament for the 1998/99 fiscal year beginning in mid-July, the
king said the programs of the Rural Development Bank, Women's
Micro Credit, Rural Self-help Fund and other poverty alleviation
programs will be carried out in a coordinated way in order to
implement the program of "Development in Each Village: Employment
in Each Family."
</P>
<P>
About 45 percent of Nepal's 21.6 million population live below
the poverty line and the majority of them live in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The government will also take appropriate steps for the
increased access of the bank credits to the poor and destitute
communities, Birendra said.
</P>
<P>
The Local Infrastructure and Agro Road Department will be set
up in the Ministry of Local Development for the integrated
development of local infrastructures and for effective
implementation of agro roads.
</P>
<P>
And the programs aimed at improving the living conditions of
the impoverished women, the ignored, exploited, ethnic and
aboriginal people and those living in the remote areas of the
country will be continued and further expanded, the king said.
</P>
<P>
He said programs will be launched for the settlement of some
100,000 bonded laborers in a systematic way and soft loans and
employment opportunities will be provided to them.
</P>
<P>
"My government has set a target to complete the debt relief
works for bonded laborers within two years," he told the MPs.
</P>
<P>
"Also within the coming fiscal year, settlement of actual
landless people will be completed in a systematic manner on their
verification," he added.
</P>
<P>
King Birendra said that in view of the interrelationship
between poverty and health, essential health services will be made
accessible to all and effective steps will be taken for the
treatment of emerging transmissible and epidemic diseases
resulting from growing urbanization.
</P>
<P>
For human resource development, he said the government will
launch programs to enhance the rights of women in political,
economic, social and legal fields through gender equality and
empowerment.
</P>
<P>
"Women and girls trafficking will be stringently controlled
with the cooperation of non-governmental organizations and the
programs for their rehabilitation will be carried out," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pre-primary and compulsory primary educational opportunities
will be expanded by mobilizing people's participation, and
continuity will be given to programs for additional educational
opportunities for female, destitute and deprived communities, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that special arrangements will be made with priority
on the increased participation of the ethnic, aboriginal and
exploited communities in technical education in such areas as
engineering, medicine, forestry and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
On economic development, the king said the government is
committed to alleviating the present economic slowdown by
increasing capital formation, production, productivity and
employment opportunities through the promotion of private
investment.
</P>
<P>
In order to develop comprehensively the country's huge water
resources, the government will introduce timely reform in the
present policy, rules and regulations so as to attract foreign and
domestic investors for its development, he said.
</P>
<P>
The campaign against such economic crimes as tax leakage and
smuggling initiated by the government will be intensified while
present reform and the monitoring system of revenue investigation
will be made more effective.
</P>
<P>
He said necessary arrangement will be made to introduce "One
Window System" in the tax administration by bringing coordination
among the various agencies dealing with value added tax (VAT) and
other taxes. He added that the VAT will be fully implemented from
the coming fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government formally introduced the VAT in November
1997 despite strong opposition from the business community.
</P>
<P>
Birendra said available resources, technologies and credit
services will be mobilized to promote small businesses and micro
enterprises as viable means for employment generation.
</P>
<P>
He said that while according priority to the programs of the
20-year Agricultural Perspective Plan (APP), the government will
launch agricultural development programs by incorporating
irrigation, technology, credit, chemical fertilizers, road and
electrification.
</P>
<P>
The APP was introduced last year with the objective of
attaining a high growth rate and contributing to poverty
alleviation.
</P>
<P>
To promote tourism and for the management of tourism
infrastructure in the country, the Nepal Tourism Promotion Board
will be made operational in the coming fiscal year, and airports
will be developed and upgraded separately in Bhairawa of western
Nepal and Biratnagar in eastern Nepal for regional and
international flights, he said.
</P>
<P>
Air service agreements will be reached with more and more
countries so as to make Nepal easily accessible to tourists, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Before and after the Visit Nepal Year '98 was launched in
January, Nepal signed air accords with a dozen countries and
regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
