<HEADLINE> UK Electricity Regulator Encourages Power Sell-Offs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Office of Electricity Regulation
(OFFER) has stepped up pressure on generating companies in Britain
to sell off some of their power stations, aiming to allow new
companies to enter the market.
</P>
<P>
Since the electricity industry in Britain was privatized in
1990, the supply side of the market has been dominated by only a
handful of generating companies.
</P>
<P>
National Power and PowerGen, Britain's two largest fossil fuel
electricity generators, must sell some of their coal-fired power
stations to reduce their "unacceptable" market power, OFFER said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Littlechild, director general of OFFER, said generators
last Winter had increased system marginal prices by 30 percent.
This could not be justified by a rise in demand or reduction in
capacity.
</P>
<P>
OFFER said that under the present arrangements, electricity
generated using coal is not as cheap as it could be were there
more players in the market.
</P>
<P>
The generators' strategy appeared to be to make a profitable
withdrawal from coal-fired generation "at the expense of customers
and also at the expense of coal as a fuel for electricity
generation," Littlechild said.
</P>
<P>
The government last week said it wanted to see power station
disposals by the large generators as part of broad-ranging reforms
to make the electricity sector more competitive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Frankfurt Stock Exchange Extends Trading Hours </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FRANKFURT, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Frankfurt Stock Exchange
Wednesday began to adopt an extended floor-trading session in a
bid to beef up its position as the largest German stock exchange
amid fierce competition.
</P>
<P>
The new floor-trading session of the Frankfurt Stock Exchange
now runs from 8:30 to 17:00 instead of from 10:30 to 13:30.
</P>
<P>
Analysts in Frankfurt said that the reform was mainly intended
to offset competition from a newly installed electronic stock
trading system called Xetra as well as from regional stock
exchanges based in seven other German cities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
