<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 18 Percent French People Declare Themselves Xenophobes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen percent of French people
openly declare themselves as xenophobes, and 40 percent say they
are drawn by racist feeling from time to time, according to a poll
published Wednesday by the daily Le Monde.
</P>
<P>
The poll was conducted by the National Consultative Commission
of Human Rights from November 24 to December 6 of 1997.
</P>
<P>
This figure puts France, along with Belgium, on top of European
countries in terms of number of people who declare themselves as
being more or less racist.
</P>
<P>
The poll also shows that a majority of those polled have
sympathy for the san papiers immigrants seeking legal residency in
France.
</P>
<P>
The poll shows that young people, people with a high
educational level, and people with higher incomes hold a more
positive and friendly feeling towards foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Le Monde said that although racism continues to haunt France, a
majority of French people are committed to the traditional value
of the country to play host to foreigners.  
</P>
</TEXT>
