<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sanctions on Angola's UNITA Go into Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A new set of sanctions on
Angola's opposition UNITA, or the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola, went into force as of midnight June 30, a
U.N. Security Council presidential statement said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The council took the measures as UNITA "has not taken the
advantage" of the council's latest resolution which allows UNITA
to finally complete its peace obligations, said this month's
council president, Russia's Sergey V. Lavrov.
</P>
<P>
The council adopted a resolution on June 12 to impose sanctions
on UNITA that include freezing UNITA's bank accounts and outlawing
its diamond trade. The movement failed to comply with the
council's demand and the council on June 24 gave it a grace period
until June 30.
</P>
<P>
But UNITA has not demilitalrized itself and transferred the four
strategic areas under its control to state administration as
requested by the 1994 Lusaka Protocol and relevant U.N.
resolutions, Lavrov said.
</P>
<P>
He said the 15 council members call on U.N. member states to
fully implement the sanction measures and reiterate their demand
to UNITA to complete its obligations.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka peace accords ended two decades of civil war after
Angola won its independence from Portugal in 1975.
</P>
<P>
The council imposed air and travel curbs on Senior UNITA
officials and closed UNITA overseas offices last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia Starts Taking Over Defense of Its Borders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Georgian border troops on Wednesday
started to take over the defense of the former Soviet republic's
maritime border, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Georgian ships will take control of the border starting July 16
in accordance with an agreement initialled with Russia in Moscow
on June 27, Interfax quoted a Georgian parliamentary official as
saying in Tbilisi.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Russian border guards will gradually
transfer defense of all sections of the Georgian border to their
Georgian counterparts, said Revaz Adamiya, chairman of the
Committee for Defense and National Security of the Georgian
parliament.
</P>
<P>
In the first stage, Georgian border guards will take over the
defense of its maritime border along the coasts of the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
During the second stage, Georgian border troops will take over
defense of its land borders with Turkey, Adamiya said.
</P>
<P>
He said Georgia, with necessary ships, personnel and coast
patrols, is ready to deal with the new task.
</P>
<P>
The United States provided Tbilisi 20 million U.S. dollars for
this purpose this year alone, and more such assistance is coming,
Adamiya said.
</P>
<P>
After the breakup of the Soviet Union, Russia retained its
military bases and troops in Gerogia. Tbilisi also agreed that
Russian troops patrol its borders with Turkey and along the
coastal borders of the Black Sea, while Georgian troops are in
charge of defense of other sections of its borders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0030 </DOCNO>
