<HEADLINE> World Traditional Healers Meeting Planned in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambian-born traditional healer
Francis Ng'ombe is planning a world conference of traditional
healers to promote the use of traditional medicines and cures.
</P>
<P>
Ng'ombe, who is president of the All Africa and Asia Medicine
Men Association, told a news conference in Harare Wednesday, "If
we do not recognize our own medicine then it will be considered
primitive, irrelevant and or witchcraft."
</P>
<P>
Ng'ombe is on a tour of southern Africa to promote the value
of traditional medicine and meet Zimbabwe's National Associations
of Traditional Healers, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
However, Ng'ombe said African leaders were hypocritical and
did not want to come out in the open in support of traditional
medicines.
</P>
<P>
He noted that there is need to explore the capabilities of
traditional medicine more by creating a center for excellence in
traditional healing.
</P>
<P>
He plans to establish a multi-million dollar modern research
center that will cater for in-depth researches in herbal and
conventional medicines.
</P>
<P>
The research center would be like a university, researching
and transforming traditional medicines into scientific medicines
sold worldwide, Ng'ombe said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
