<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tripartite Alliance Remains Important: Mandela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela Wednesday attached great importance to the ruling
African National Congress (ANC)'s alliance with the South African
Communist Party (SACP) and the Congress of South African Trade
Unions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the SACP's 10th congress here, Mandela said the
congress came at a critical time -- as the alliance was being
questioned.
</P>
<P>
"It comes when the assault on our alliance has reached an all
time high. It comes at a time when opposition forces are
attacking our very existence."
</P>
<P>
However, Mandela said, the role of the alliance was as
important as ever in continuing on the path of reconstruction and
development to better the lives of the poorest South Africans.
</P>
<P>
The SACP, established in 1921, had been working hand in hand
with the ANC in fight against apartheid for more than half a
century. It has become a member of the ruling alliance since
apartheid was abolished in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The SACP congress also came at a time when a vision of and for
the poor in the new millennium needed to be programmatically
defined, Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela was also presented the Chris Hani Award for Peace by
the SACP at the congress.
</P>
<P>
Hani, former leader of the SACP, was assassinated by apartheid
extremists on April 10, 1993.
</P>
<P>
The five-day SACP congress will review progress made in the
country since the first non-racial elections in 1994 in addition
to assessment of the party's performance since its last congress
in April 1995.
</P>
<P>
The delegates will also elect a ne w central committee of the
party and its leaders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
