<HEADLINE> UN Compensation Commission Approves First Corporate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Compensation
Commission (UNCC) approved here Wednesday first corporate claims
to award four companies a total of 187.5 million U.S. dollars for
their losses in Iraq following Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The four foreign construction companies originally sought an
amount of up to two billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
At the end of its three-day meeting, the UNCC Governing Council
ruled that companies which were not paid by Iraq can only be
helped from a Gulf War compensation fund if the claims are for
goods or services delivered within three months of the start of
the war.
</P>
<P>
The decision to rule out claims for earlier contracts will act
as a guideline for deciding on scores of further claims by foreign
businesses which worked in Iraq before the invasion of Kuwait on
August 2, 1990, a senior official of the governing council said.
</P>
<P>
"They studied the practice of payment in Iraq, they looked at
how the payment system worked, they didn't want to choose an
arbitrary (cut-off) date," said Mojtaba Kazazi, secretary of the
commission's Governing Council.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Kazazi said the commission decided to grant only
187.5 million dollars out of two billion dollars sought by the
four companies. The commission's decision is final and cannot be
appealed.
</P>
<P>
The companies were named as Continental Construction Ltd of
India, Kuwait's Gulf Cable and Electrical Co, Hyundai Construction
of South Korea and Technopromexport of Russia.
</P>
<P>
The UNCC was established in accordance with U.N. Security
Council resolutions 687 and 692 (1991) to pay compensation for
losses and damages suffered by individuals, corporations,
governments and international organizations as a direct result of
Iraq's invasion and occupation of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Funds to pay compensation are drawn from the Compensation Fund,
also established under Security Council resolution 692.
</P>
<P>
The fund receives up to 30 percent of the revenue from the
export of Iraqi oil under the "oil-for-food" mechanism.  
</P>
</TEXT>
