<HEADLINE> U.S. to Pursue Diplomacy to Solve S.Asia Nuclear Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States, while
imposing sanctions on India and Pakistan for their nuclear tests,
would continue to pursue "discreet" diplomacy to dissuade them
from further developing nuclear programs, U.S. Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press breakfast, Talbott said diplomacy "is
already under way," and he indicated to intensify and accelerate
the pace so that it would "ultimately produce some results
during the months ahead."
</P>
<P>
But he said the diplomacy "needs to have an element of
cooperation" with both India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Talbott said the U.S. strategy was to seek to persuade India
and Pakistan that it was in their own interests to refrain from
building nuclear weapons or producing fissile material.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that India and Pakistan will both be safer, they
will be better off, if they were to apply after the fact of
these tests the kind of restraint and discipline and
forward-looking wisdom that we wish they had applied before they
made the mistake of the tests," he said.
</P>
<P>
Talbott said in the coming months, U.S. officials will discuss
world's concern over the nuclear tests with both governments
"through discreet but not by any means secret channel."
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, Talbott has met both Indian special envoy
Jaswant Singh and Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmed to
discuss the nuclear issue, and he said he expected more such
meetings in the future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
