<HEADLINE> New Israeli-Lebanese Swap Depends on Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Committee of the
Red Cross (ICRC) said Wednesday that a new swap deal between
Lebanon and Israel depends on the information of a missing Israeli
pilot.
</P>
<P>
Any information about Israel's air force navigator Ron Arad
will help the two countries strike another deal, under which
Lebanese prisoners held by Israel may be freed, Jean Jacques
Fresard, ICRC's chief delegate, told reporters after a meeting
with Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz.
</P>
<P>
Arad's plane was shot down by Lebanese guerrillas in south
Lebanon in 1986. He was believed to be captured alive by the
guerrillas, but no clear information has been provided on his
whereabouts ever since.
</P>
<P>
Israel claims that the Hezbollah (Party of God) is keeping Arad
in its prison or his body if he is dead. But the anti-Israel
Muslim group has neither confirmed nor denied the allegation.
</P>
<P>
Fresard called on any groups or individuals having relevant
information about the pilot to contact with the ICRC or the
Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
He said that his organization is ready to play a role in
brokering a possible new swap deal.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC has recently achieved a deal between the two sides,
under which Israel last Wednesday returned to Lebanon the bodies
of 40 guerrillas and freed 60 prisoners in exchange for the
remains of a soldier killed last September in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 117 more Lebanese are still held by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Since Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer "security zone" in
 south Lebanon in 1985 to allegedly protect its northern areas
from cross-border guerrilla attacks, Lebanese resistance forces
have been fighting to oust the Israeli troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
