<HEADLINE> Businessmen of Cyprus' Rival Communities Call for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Greek and Turkish Cypriot business
representatives have called for increased contact and cooperation
between the two communities on the island.
</P>
<P>
The call was contained in a joint statement issued at the end
of a two-day meeting of business representatives of the two
Cypriot communities in Oslo, Norwegian capital, which was a
follow-up to a meeting in Brussels last November, Cyprus News
Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement stressed the need for particular steps "to relax
and eventually lift all restrictions on the free movement of
people, goods and services and increase contacts in business,
cultural and sports areas."
</P>
<P>
"Such contacts should be encouraged by the political
authorities on both sides," the bicommunal business
representatives said.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to work together toward realizing a number of
projects such as the restoration of the Apostolos Andreas
Monastery, in the Turkish-controlled northeastern Karpas
peninsula, and the Hala Sultan Mosque in the government-controlled
southern areas of the island.
</P>
<P>
Other projects include the enhancement of telecommunication
services, joint environmental efforts starting with a solid waste
disposal project and joint trade and economic ventures in areas
such as dairy products, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
The two communities' businessmen also propose "the holding of
a tournament of local sports clubs and cultural events, starting
with the sports tournament in November."
</P>
<P>
They called for the negotiation process between the two
communities to move forward and pledged to "work to persuade the
political leadership of both sides to support these initiatives."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since Turkish
troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in
1974 in the aftermath of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash has suspended the
bicommunal contacts since last December to protest against a
European Union decision to begin accession talks with the Cypriot
government in March this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
