<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes U.S. Position on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government welcomed
Wednesday the statements by U.S. Ambassador to the U.N. Bill
Richardson, which urged Turkey to work to break the deadlock in
the Cyprus peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased with the comments by Ambassador Bill
Richardson since they back the U.N. resolutions and the fresh
effort to break the current deadlock," government spokesman
Christos Stylianides said at his press briefing here.
</P>
<P>
In a statement at the Security Council, Richardson called on
Turkey to cooperate with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and his
special advisor Diego Cordovez in their efforts to promote a
comprehensive settlement to the Cyprus dispute.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated the U.S. support for U.N. efforts to achieve
a just and lasting settlement based on a bizonal and bicommunal
federation of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides noted that the statement reflected the unified
position of U.N. Security Council members and backed Cordovez's
new attempt to break the deadlock in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez is due to arrive here Thursday for talks with Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides and the Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus peace process has been stalled since last summer
when Denktash quited the U.N.-sponsored peace talks with
Clerides, the Greek Cypriot leader, to protest against the
decision by the European Union (EU) to start accession
talks with the Clerides-led Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has demanded the recognition of his breakaway entity
in northern Cyprus and halt of the EU entry talks as precondition
for resuming the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the divided
island as a bizonal and bicommunal federation through peace
talks, but so far no tangible results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
