<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Officials Defend Spending on Nuclear Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A private research group said
the U.S. is spending 35 billion U.S. dollars on nuclear weapons
annually even after the Cold War ended, while the State Department
defended nuclear programs on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said the weapons
deterred the Soviet Union and the fact that the program was
expensive "should not come as a surprise."
</P>
<P>
Since the birth of the atomic weapons program in 1940, a total
of 5.5 trillion U.S. dollars was spent through 1996, the private
research group reported.
</P>
<P>
The cost is 29 percent of all U.S. military spending and almost
11 percent of all government spending through the 52 years.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said administration officials had not had a chance to
assess the accuracy of the Brookings estimates.
</P>
<P>
But he added, "It was worth the expense; communism was worth
deterring through a combined policy of containment and
modernization of nuclear forces."
</P>
<P>
Stephen Schwartz, chief of the four-year study project, said
that the audit was not undertaken to determine whether the U.S.
nuclear force was worth the expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Calculating costs for nuclear research, development,
deployment, command and control, defenses and dismantlement, the
audit was designed to set the stage for "an honest and fully
informed debate to begin."
</P>
<P>
Schwartz wrote in the report that the "impetus to manufacture
and deploy large numbers of nuclear weapons gathered strength
because nuclear weapons were considered less expensive than
conventional strength."
</P>
<P>
Had the true costs been known, he wrote, there almost certainly
would have been a debate about the wisdom of the continued buildup
of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The study found that only seven percent of the total cost for
the nuclear weapons went for development and manufacture of the
actual warheads.
</P>
<P>
Development of weapons system, such as bombers and missiles,
and the infrastructure to facilitate their use made up 86 percent
of the expenses, while much of the rest went for cleanup.
</P>
<P>
"In the end," Schwartz said, "cleanup costs may be as much as
the weapons cost in the first place."
</P>
<P>
The stockpile of the nuclear weapons has the equivalent
explosive force of about 120,000 Hiroshima bombs although new
weapons are no longer being produced, Shwartz said.
</P>
<P>
He added that 4.5 billion U.S. dollars were spent annually to
keep the nuclear stockpile reliable.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP to Spend $52M  for Helping Angolan Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government and the
World Food Program (WFP) signed an agreement here Wednesday on
providing humanitarian assistance to the refugees in 1998/99 in
the war-ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, WFP will provide the 539,500 war-created
refugees with humanitarian assistance worth 52 million U.S.
Dollars including 79,346 tons of foods during the year from March
1998 to February 1999.
</P>
<P>
WFP will also work with the Angolan government to facilitate
the rehabilitation of these refugees, encouraging them to return
home earlier.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the Angolan government will take
up some expenditures in helping the refugees, mainly providing
low-priced fuels to them. The cost in this area will amount to
six million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
During the signing ceremony, Angolan Minister of Assistance
and Social Reintegration Albino Malungo said that the
implementation of the agreement will offer relief to the urgent
demand of the refugees for foods and will help them return home
in time.
</P>
<P>
WFP is the major structure of the United Nations in providing
foods to the Angolan refugees. It gives help to Angolan people
in health care, such as fighting against malnutrition,
tuberculosis and some epidemics in the country. It also takes an
active part in helping the war orphans and the street children in
the southern African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
