<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Emerges Biggest Importer of Nigeria's Crude </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Despite cold bilateral political
relations, the U.S. has replaced Western European as the biggest
importer of Nigeria's crude oil in 1997, the Central Bank of
Nigeria has said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in its newly released 1997 annual report that
the U.S. bought 267 million barrels of crude oil from Nigeria
last year, which accounted for 34.6 percent of Nigeria's total
export.
</P>
<P>
The figure is 11 million barrels up from 1996 but 4.9 million
barrels down from the level of 1995, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the share of Western Europe in Nigeria's total
crude oil export declined from 36.3 percent in 1996 to 27.6
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In all, Nigeria exported 213 million barrels of crude oil to
Western Europe in 1997, compared to 270.7 million barrels a year
before.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the upward trend in the share of Asia's
crude oil import from Nigeria which began in 1995 was sustained
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The region's share which stood at 11.5 percent in 1995 went up
to 16 percent in 1996, and rose further to 17.6 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Purchase of Nigeria's crude oil by African countries stood at
51.9 million barrels in 1997, accounting for a share of 5.7
percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, Africa's biggest oil producer and member of the
Organization of Petroleum Export Countries (OPEC), produces a
little more than two million barrels of crude oil a day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
