<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Urges Control on Soft PVC Toys for Babies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission urged
Wednesday European governments to check against baby toys made of
soft PVC that are blamed for releasing hazardous chemicals.
</P>
<P>
European Union scientists claimed that two of the six chemical
additives in PVC could pose long-term health risks if sucked by
young children.
</P>
<P>
The additives are DINP and DEHP, both of the family of
phthalates. Animal tests showed that they are toxic and can cause
cancer when ingested.
</P>
<P>
But the European Commission, the executive body of the
15-nation EU, voted on June 10 against a total ban on phthalates,
arguing that it is hard to gauge the rate at which phthalates
migrate from PVC to human bodies.
</P>
<P>
European Consumer Affairs Commissioner Emma Bonino, however,
recommended a ban on toys designed to be chewed or sucked.
</P>
<P>
Denmark and Spain have already withdrawn certain types of
teething rings from markets while Austria, that is taking over the
rotating presidency of the EU, notified the commission of its
intention to ban the use of all phthalates in toys that are to be
chewed or sucked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
