<HEADLINE> Iran to Increase Power Generating Capacity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Iran is boosting its power industry,
expecting to greatly increase electricity generating capacity for
the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Iran's power generating capacity stands at 25,000 megawatts,
ranking the 21st largest producer of electricity in the world,
Iranian Deputy Energy Minister Mohammad Malaki said here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Iran's electric output is expected to reach 105 billion
kilowatts-hour this year, 9 billion kilowatts-hour more than that
last year, the official news agency IRNA quoted Malaki as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that his country should increase power generating
capacity by 1,600 to 2,000 megawatts annually in the next 10 years
to meet the needs for power.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iranian Minister of Energy Habibollah Bitaraf said
on Tuesday in Chaloos in northern Mazadaran Province that Iran's
energy consumption rises by an annual 8.9 percent every year, 3.9
percentage points more than the figure predicted in the second
five-year development plan from 1995 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to Malaki, Iran exports 20 million U.S. dollars worth
of electricity to Turkey, Armenia and Azerbaijan each year and its
power network will be linked with that of Turkmenistan by the end
of the current Iranian year on March 20, 1999.
</P>
<P>
He said the country earns a yearly 25-30 million dollars from
exporting power equipment and products to Syria, Libya and
Central Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Malaki said that Iran is to host the 4th power industry fair on
July 6-10. Some 165 private and 55 public companies of Iran, and
companies from Russia, Britain and Syria are expected to take part
in the fair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
