<HEADLINE> Jordan, Iraq to Discuss Building Oil Pipeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Minister of Energy and
Mineral Resources Saleh Hourani left here Wednesday for Iraq
to discuss building a pipeline in order to lower the cost of
Iraq's oil supply to the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will talk about the continued implementation of
the deal signed in December 1997, in which Iraq agreed to provide
Jordan with 4.8 million tonnes of oil and oil products this year
at reduced prices.
</P>
<P>
In order to achieve a more economic and quicker way of
transporting oil from Iraq, the two sides are exploring the
possibility of constructing a 750-kilometer-long pipeline between
the Iraqi city Haditha and a Jordanian oil refinery in Zarqa, some
20 kilometers northeast to Amman.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Iraqi oil supply is carried out by oil tankers,
at the rate of 400 trucks a day, costing Jordan 50 million
U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
The planned pipeline, estimated to cost some 250 million
dollars, is expected to save money for Jordan in a long-term view.
</P>
<P>
During the talks in Baghdad, Hourani will also discuss the
prospects for jointly developing oil fields near the
Jordanian-Iraqi border.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been the sole oil provider for Jordan for years, and
it sells oil to Jordan at a pricer much lower than that on the
international market. In 1998, Iraqi oil is sold to the kingdom at
16.8 dollars per barrel, down from 19.15 dollars in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
