<HEADLINE> Lisbon Conference to Address Youth Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A conference organized by
Portugal and the United Nations to deal with issues facing youth
will be held in Lisbon, Portugal, next month, it was announced
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 ministers in charge of youth affairs are expected
to gather to discuss unprecedented rural-to-urban migration,
unemployment, poverty, armed conflicts, juvenile violence and
sexual exploitation, the U.N. Department of Public Information
(DPI) said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Other issues on the agenda are opportunities for education,
training, health and social services.
</P>
<P>
John Langmore, an official with the U.N. Economic and Social
Affairs Department, said it is the fist global meeting on youth at
the ministerial level held since the founding of the U.N. in 1945.
</P>
<P>
The conference will decide on further ways of implementing the
World Program of Action for Youth to the Year 2000 adopted by the
U.N. General Assembly in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The program focuses in particular on measures to strengthen
national capacities regarding youth and to increase the quality
and quantity of opportunities available to young people.
</P>
<P>
The world youth population, defined by the U.N. as the age
group between 15 and 24 years old, was estimated in 1995 at 1
billion, or 18 percent of the total world population. Most of them
live in developing countries and their numbers are expected to
rise well into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Due to be opened by Portuguese President Jorge Sampaio and U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan on August 8, the conference will end
on August 12, the DPI said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
