<HEADLINE> Nigeria Military Dismisses Rumor on Former </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's defense authorities
Wednesday opened up on the rumor surrounding the fate of former
Chief of General Staff Lt.-Gen. Oladipo Diya and other officers,
saying that their conditions are okay.
</P>
<P>
"Lt.-Gen. Diya and the others are hale and hearty where they
are kept," Rear Admiral Festus Porseni, defense chief of
administration, said at the Defense Headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
Diya and five others were sentenced to death by a special
military tribunal last April for an alleged plot to overthrow the
late General Sani Abacha government.
</P>
<P>
The sentence has since been submitted to the country's highest
policy-making body, the Provisional Ruling Council (PRC), to
ratify.
</P>
<P>
There were reports earlier this week that the coup plotters
had been kidnapped or even executed not long after the sudden
death of Abacha on June 8.
</P>
<P>
Dismissing the rumors, Porseni said "since the completion of
the tribunal, the PRC had not met to ratify the sentences of the
individual convicts," the News Agency of Nigeria reported.
</P>
<P>
He said such rumors at this time of national reconciliation
when the nation's doors were being opened to many outsiders were
uncalled for.
</P>
<P>
"Henceforth the spread of such rumors shall be visited by the
long arm of the law," he said, appealing that the seeming peace
in the country should be allowed to remain.
</P>
<P>
However, Porseni admitted that the movement of the coup
plotters from one place to another was normal and could be done
according to security implications.
</P>
<P>
There have been appeals for the release of Diya and others
involved in the coup plot since the death of Abacha.  
</P>
