<HEADLINE> Turkey, Syria Seek Ways to Normalize Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Syria are discussing ways
of normalizing their relations, the Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to open a way for dialog in relations frozen for
a long time," Turkish Foreign Undersecretary Korkmaz Haktanir told
reporters Wednesday after talks held here with his Syrian
counterpart Adnan Omran.
</P>
<P>
"This is a long and difficult process. The matters being taken
up are extremely sensitive," Haktanir said, adding that the
terrorism issue, which is a major obstacle to the normalization of
the ties, has been discussed in detail.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Haktanir and Omran discussed ways of
returning the troubled relations between the two neighbors to
normal, the semi-official news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Omran, who arrived here Tuesday on a three-day trip, is the
most senior Syrian official visiting Turkey in four years. He is
expected to meet with Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are trying to set up concrete channels,
including arranging high-level visits, to solve their thorny
problems, Haktanir said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Syria have long been at odds due to differences over
sharing of water resources and alleged Damascus' support for
Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party, which has been fighting
since 1984 for a Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey bordering
Syria. 
</P>
