<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daewoo Manufactures Cars in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Aiming to increase its share of
Egypt's booming car market, South Korean auto giant Daewoo
unveiled first two locally produced cars Wednesday night at a
ceremony held against the breathtaking backdrop of the Great
Pyramids.
</P>
<P>
The two cars, Lanos 1500 cc and Leganza 2000 cc, were
manufactured in Daewoo's first joint automobile factory built with
an Egyptian partner, the Aboul Fotouh Establishment, which is one
of Egypt's top five corporations.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture, named Daewoo Motor Egypt S.A.E., is a
30,000-square-meter factory constructed on the fringe of the Sixth
of October City, about 26 kilometers east of the capital city
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo contributed 60 percent of the 45 million U.S. dollars of
total investment for building the factory, while the rest of the
came from its Egyptian partner.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian-S.Korean partnership followed a couple of
similar marriages between local companies and world-famed auto
names, such as Germany's Daimles-Benz and Hyundai Co., South
Korea's No.1 automaker.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua Wednesday, Chairman of the Aboul
Fotouh Establishment Houssam Aboul Fotouh expressed confidence
about the success of the joint venture in an increasingly
competitive market. He dismissed the concern about a saturated car
market in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
"There are so many varieties of passenger cars competing
against each other in Egypt. But what we are viewing at is a niche
market," he said.
</P>
<P>
As one of the biggest car factories in Egypt, the factory takes
aim at Egypt's expanding middle class by producing low-price
economic and luxurious passenger cars.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo's President and CEO Byung-Ho Kang explained that the two
cars are Daewoo's latest models in the category of economic and
luxurious cars with competitive prices. No prices were disclosed
for the local sales of the two models, bu they sell for 10,000
dollars and 25,000 dollars in Poland, the biggest overseas market
for Daewoo.
</P>
<P>
Kang predicted that the combined production of the two cars
would exceed 3,500 units by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
He added that the joint venture will also import two other
models which are Nubira 1600 cc-16 valve and the smaller cozy
Matiz that has "fascinated the Koreans" since it first hit the
market at the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
The company is also planning to manufacture commercial vehicles
such as microbuses, pickups, trucks starting from next year.
</P>
<P>
H. I. Lee, managing director of Daewoo Motor Egypt, predicted
that the company will gain at least 15 percent share of the
Egyptian market within a year.
</P>
<P>
Kang said the new company was part of Daewoo's efforts to shift
its production overseas in the face of a declining domestic
market, which has shrunk by 50 percent within less than a year.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo, which sold 1.3 million passenger cars worldwide in 1997
and earned 4 billion dollars in revenues, boasts a bigger overseas
market than its top domestic competitor Hyundai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
