<HEADLINE> Democratic Convention Planners Postpone Philadelphia Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Democrats looking for a site for
their national convention in 2000 left Philadelphia rather than
face pickets in an acrimonious transit strike.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Democratic National Committee's site-advisory
group withdrew hours after their arrival Tuesday afternoon for a
three-day visit, although they promised they'd be back to check
out the city once they wouldn't have to run the risk of crossing
picket lines.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, as Democrats, every single member of the committee
is a supporter of organized labor and believes in the principles
of organized labor," The Associated Press quoted Joe Andrew,
chairman of the group, as saying. "The committee's interest here
is making sure that Philadelphia has as good a shot at this thing
as any of the finalists."
</P>
<P>
The DNC committee is visiting six other candidates -- Boston,
Denver, Los Angeles, Miami, Minneapolis and New Orleans -- for its
national convention, which amounts to a 150 million dollar
windfall for the winner.
</P>
<P>
Philadelphia had three days of touring and selling planned:
visits to the Independence Hall and fancy restaurants, parades by
police cruisers, fire trucks and the Mummers and the pitch itself.
</P>
<P>
But the Southeastern Pennsylvania Transit Authority (SEPTA) and
the Transport Workers Union Local 234 were in negotiations Tuesday
when talks suddenly went sour and union local president Steve
Brookens stormed out of the negotiations. Some 200 workers marched
down Market Street to set up pickets near the Independence Hall,
where the DNC group were to arrive for a tour at 5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Edward G. Rendell said the committee had already decided
to leave town.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want them to have to decide who's right and who's
wrong," said Rendell.
</P>
<P>
The strike started on June 1 during the Republican
site-selection committee visit, but the SEPTA strikers did not
picket the Republicans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
