<HEADLINE> Prices Hike After VAT Introduced in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Prices of goods in Dar es
Salaam suddenly increased Wednesday, the first day for Tanzania
to introduce the Value Added Tax (VAT), despite President
Benjamin Mkapa's warnings to punish unscrupulous businessmen.
</P>
<P>
The price hikes of a lot of goods have nothing to do with VAT,
whose primary objective is to expand the tax base and enhance tax
collection in the country.
</P>
<P>
In Kijitonyama and Milocheni areas, a kilogram of sugar was
sold at 500 Shillings (about 75 U.S. cents), up from 400
Shillings, while the retailed price of a bottle of beer in bars
and clubs increased from 400 Shillings to 600 Shillings. Rice
prices have also soared.
</P>
<P>
Petty traders in the kiosks along the Morogoro Road in the
capital city have also raised the prices of the consumer goods,
some of which are not among the list of goods under the VAT
system.
</P>
<P>
Speaking through the radio to the nation on Tuesday evening,
President Mkapa assured that VAT, charged with a rate of 20
percent, will neither disrupt the economy nor reduce people's
purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said that several items are not included in the VAT,
noting that such items are crucial to the survival of low-income
earners.
</P>
<P>
He listed them as medicine and medical instruments for both
human beings and livestock, medical services and treatment, main
food stuffs including maize, rice, wheat, banana, cassava,
unprocessed meat and fish.
</P>
<P>
Education services for registered institutions, books,
journals and newspapers, water services, petroleum products,
public transport, house rent are some of the goods and services
exempted from VAT.
</P>
<P>
From July 1, it is forbidden to charge sales tax, stamp duty
and entertainment tax, the president said.
</P>
<P>
He asked the public to inform the police or revenue officials
of any unreasonable price hikes.
</P>
<P>
"Businessmen who raise their prices for exempted goods like
foodstuff should be taken to task," he warned.
</P>
<P>
A lot of traders just could not explain what VAT is while some
others are spreading rumors that prices of all goods have
skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
Mwima Kilongo of the Makumbusho Trading Center said that she
did not know what VAT means and asked the authorities concerned
to give more education on VAT "even by using churches and
mosques." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Federal Reserve Keeps Interest Rates Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- As the U.S. economic growth
could be finally slowing down, the Federal Reserve decided
Wednesday to leave short-term interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Fed's policy-making panel, the Federal Open Market
Committee, concluded its two-day close-door meeting, signaling it
had left the benchmark rate on overnight loans between banks
unchanged at 5.5 percent. It's been at that level since a quarter
of a percentage point increase in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
The result was widely anticipated and financial markets showed
little reaction. Raising U.S. rates would have risked
destabilizing already-rocky Asian financial markets by giving
investors another reason to transfer their money to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the U.S. economy appears to be slowing on its own from
the robust annual growth rates of 5.4 percent in the first quarter
of this year. And consumer price inflation, running at a 1.5
percent annual rate during the first five months of the year,
appears well-contained.
</P>
<P>
On Wall Street, reports the Japanese government will propose
major tax cuts boosted stock prices. In early afternoon the Dow
Jones industrial average was up 55 points, hovering about the
9,000 mark.
</P>
<P>
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, in his last
congressional testimony on the economy, on June 10, expressed his
concern that a shortage of labor would produce wage pressures that
would in turn produce faster price increases.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment in April and May sank to a 28-year-low of 4.3
percent as a consequence consumer confidence, as measured by the
New York-based Conference Board, hit a 29-year high in June.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan noted that higher interest rates may be necessary to
guard against a buildup of pressures, but gave no hint that the
increase was imminent. Economists said Greenspan and other Fed
officials are worrisome that raising U.S. rates will touch off
renewed financial turbulence in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there are signs, from declining factory orders to a
deteriorating trade deficit to a buildup in inventories of unsold
goods, that U.S. growth is set to slow significantly.
</P>
<P>
And the strike at General Motors started on June 5 has already
pushed up first-time claims for unemployment benefits. July
employment and industrial production figures likely will reflect a
larger impact.
</P>
<P>
Most economists expect the economy's growth rate to slow from a
rapid 5.4 percent in the first three months of the year to
something around 2 percent for the rest of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Donors to Discuss Help for S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- International aid donors are to meet
in London on July 15 and 16 to discuss help for Sierra Leone, a
report reaching here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The government of Sierra Leone had a funding gap of about 34
billion Leones (22 million U.S. Dollars) and hoped donors would
fill, the report quoted Sierra Leone's Finance Minister James
Jonah as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the donors had made no firm commitments so far, the
minister disclosed in his budget speech to parliament Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The IMF (International Monetary Fund) is convening a donors'
conference meeting in London on July 15 and 16 to appeal for
funding to fill our budgetary gap and for our balance of payments
requirements," Jonah said.
</P>
<P>
The budget covers the period from February 17 to the end of
1998.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone has been in a poor situation since the May 25
coup last year that ousted the legitimate government of President
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
The junta that seized power through the coup was overthrown
last February, followed by the restoration of Kabbah's government
with the help of the west African peacekeeping force ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
However, the ousted junta has left the country's central bank
clean of all foreign exchange, according to a central bank
official.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed official said that the central bank now has less
than 5,000 U.S. Dollars in currency reserves in its vaults.
</P>
<P>
The deteriorating situation is partly attributed to the ban of
diamond and gold mining in the country, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
Diamonds are Sierra Leone's main export. Kabbah has banned
mining activities until a proper mining code can be brought in
and also because the security situation is still precarious
outside the capital Freetown, especially in the main mining
areas.
</P>
<P>
The lack of foreign currency has slowed the import of
essential goods and the government has appealed for help.
</P>
<P>
"President Kabbah has had to beg in the past few days for the
World Bank to provide Sierra Leone with five million (U.S.)
Dollars so that the central bank can continue to operate," said
presidential spokesman Septimus Kaika.
</P>
<P>
"We hope they will give us the money soon and not wait until
September, when officials from the World Bank and IMF resume
talks with the government to get programs going again in the
country," said the central bank official.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the country's two main banks,
Barclays and Standard Chartered, are also suffering from the lack
of currency. 
</P>
