<HEADLINE> EU Lifts Ban on Fresh Fishery Imports from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
announced Wednesday that it has lifted the ban on fresh fishery
imports from Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the delegation of European Commission (EC) in
Dar es Salaam said that the EC is pleased to announce that the EC
import ban has been lifted for all fresh fishery products from
Tanzania after taking advice from the EC Veterinary Committee.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the decision, which becomes effective
on July 1, reversed earlier measures taken in January this year
to limit the import of fishery products.
</P>
<P>
The ban was imposed because EU countries feared that through
imports of fresh fish fillets from Tanzania and other African
countries, the cholera epidemic that erupted in areas at Lake
Victoria and other African regions will affect their food.
</P>
<P>
But EU has demanded that health certificate must accompany
each consignment of fishery products.
</P>
<P>
"European Union member states shall be in a position to refuse
all consignments not accompanied by this declaration from July 1,
this year.
</P>
<P>
"From July 1 of 1998, Tanzania Fishery Division of the
Ministry of Natural Resources and Tourism is considered by the EC
as the competent authority responsible for the enforcement of the
EC regulations regarding hygienic conditions," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
President Benjamin Mkapa, in a letter to President of the
European Commission Jacques Santer, welcomed the decision. Mkapa
expressed hopes that the European Union will further help
Tanzania develop its economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to reports, similar bans on Kenya, Uganda
and Mozambique have also been lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
