<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Plans "Bridge Bank" Scheme to Settle Loan Mess </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government and the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) on Thursday mapped out a
"bridge bank" plan aimed at settling the Japanese banking sector's
bad loan mess.
</P>
<P>
The bridge-bank plan is intended to prevent bank failures from
disrupting the rest of the banking system and the economy by
placing failed banks under government control. They are turned
into bridge banks that would continue extending loans to sound
borrowers.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Finance Minister Hikaru Matsunaga told a news
conference that the bridge-bank scheme will be limited to failures
that occur until March 2001.
</P>
<P>
The plan also includes measures to promote the disposal of bad
loans as well as steps to reinforce inspection and supervision of
financial institutions by the newly established Financial
Supervisory Agency (FSA).
</P>
<P>
The government and the LDP hope the plan will help restore
confidence, both domestically and internationally, in a recovery
of the long-stalled Japanese economy, government and LDP officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's bridge-bank system is said to be modeled on a United
States scheme in 1987 to deal with financial failures.
</P>
<P>
Bridge banks would be subsidiaries of a holding company to be
set up by the semi-governmental Deposit Insurance Corp.
</P>
<P>
Independent panels will be established to determine which loans
bridge banks may inherit from collapsed institutions.
</P>
<P>
Japanese business leaders welcomed the plan, saying the scheme
could help protect failed banks' borrowers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yen Devaluation No Alarm for Philippines: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Finance Secretary Edgardo
Espiritu Thursday said there is no cause for alarm over the
devaluation of the Japanese yen, adding that this is even more
advantageous to the Philippine economy.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu explained that the devaluation of the Japanese yen
would even put the Philippine finances into a better position, as
it will reduce significantly its foreign debts in the Japanese
currency.
</P>
<P>
He said a huge amount of the country's debts are in yen, making
it easier for the country to settle these with a weaker Japanese
currency.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he stressed that the Estrada administration
is determined to keep its limit on domestic borrowings, ruling out
the possibility the country will still be floating treasury bills
to raise additional funds for the government.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said the government will only be able to incur around
2 billion pesos (50 million U.S. dollars) or less in domestic
borrowings to maintain its limit.
</P>
<P>
He expressed apprehension that floating more treasury bills and
increasing the government's domestic borrowing could further push
inflation upward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
