<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Urges More Open Australian Market for Textiles, Autos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Trade Organization (WTO)
has called on Australia to continue trade liberalization measures
and internal structural reforms to further open its market to
foreign textiles and automobiles.
</P>
<P>
The economic reforms launched by Australia in the early 1990s
have led to a higher growth of the gross domestic product (GDP)
and productivity, and to lower unemployment, said the WTO here
Thursday, in a report reviewing Australian trade policy.
</P>
<P>
The WTO said Australia has maintained the highest annual GDP
growth in the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD) since the early 1990s,.
</P>
<P>
"The economic reforms, including tariff reform, a reduction in
subsidies and the deregulation and privatization of many services
sectors, have improved the competitiveness of Australian business and
stimulated exports," said the WTO.
</P>
<P>
"Despite these benefits, Australia appears hesitant about pushing
ahead with reforms, especially for industries that continue to be
relatively heavily protected, such as textiles and clothing and the
automotive sector," the WTO said.
</P>
<P>
The WTO Secretariat report and a policy statement prepared by
the Australian government provided the basis for a review by the
WTO of Australia's trade policies and practices when delegates
from the WTO's 132 members met, on June 30 and July 2, to assess
the report and the statement.
</P>
<P>
"It is crucial that the trade and structural reform process be
continued and completed to ensure strong growth in the long run,"
the WTO said. "This would also help reduce Australia's
unemployment rate, which is still above eight percent."
</P>
<P>
"Hesitation over pushing through further reforms create
anomalies and distortions in the tariff and assistance structure,
and may give mixed signals to producers and consumers about the
government's commitment to future reforms and their direction,"
the report said.
</P>
<P>
"There is a need for ongoing reform to address regulatory
measures and structural rigidities that continue to impair the
competitiveness of Australian industry," the WTO report
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
