<HEADLINE> Moscow Cancels Trust Accord with Gazprom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Moscow has taken back the 35 percent
equity share it had in the gas giant, Gazprom, which was held in
trust managed by Gazprom's influential president.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko instructed Deputy Prime
Minister Boris Nemtsov to announce the abolition of the contract
for trust management with Rem Vyakhirev.
</P>
<P>
The instruction was given at a meeting late on Thursday of the
state's representatives to Gazprom, the world's biggest gas
producer.
</P>
<P>
The contract between Moscow and Gazprom was signed on December
22, 1997, and was to end on March 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The government also ordered the State Tax Service to seize
property of Gazprom.
</P>
<P>
The move was reportedly triggered by Gazprom's defaulting on
current tax payments to the federal budget. According to Deputy
Prime Minister Oleg Sysuyev, the company had paid only a third of
its tax payment by June.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov told reporters after the government meeting: "If
Gazprom repays taxes, everything will be OK."
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Oleg Sysuyev said "nobody, including
Gazprom, will be allowed, in a shameless way, not to pay taxes."
</P>
<P>
Moscow has begun putting pressure on companies in tax arrears
to pay up. The action is part of a government austerity package
aimed at avoiding financial collapse.
</P>
<P>
The government on Thursday acted against five oil companies by
restricting their access to pipelines used for exporting
oil. Another four companies which owned the state about 1.15
billion rubles (185 million U.S. dollars) were penalized Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) is currently considering
a request by the Russian government for a stabilization loan of 10
to 15 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
