<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair on
Thursday condemned a spate of arson attacks in Northern Ireland as
"barbarous behavior."
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman said Blair had discussed with
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam about the arson and said he
wanted to "go to underline his support for the whole peace
process."
</P>
<P>
"He said this sort of barbarous behavior is totally
unacceptable in this country. Violence from this or any other
quarter will have no effect whatsoever on the government's
policies," the spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Ten Roman Catholic churches were damaged in a wave of arson
attacks across the province, police said. Security forces were
linking loyalist terror group the Liberation Volunteer Forces
(LVF) with the attacks on the Catholic churches across the
province.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Blair told his ministers at Thursday's
cabinet meeting that the way forward in Northern Ireland was
through "dialogue and democracy, not intimidation and thuggery."
