<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Japanese ambassador to India
Hiroshi Hirabayashi said Thursday that Japanese investment to the
country might slow down in the short term as the business
community is apprehensive of the negative signals from India.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign investors, including those from Japan may at best like
to wait and see and at worst pull out" due to the negative shadow
cast by the recent Indian nuclear tests, deterioration in security
environment, looming sanctions, self-reliance rhetoric and
spillover effects of the East Asian financial turmoil," he said.
</P>
<P>
"While government officials are giving mixed signals, we are
hearing about 'saying good-bye to the World Trade Organization
(WTO)' and boycott of foreign goods from some non-government
quarters," he said at a meeting organized by the Federation of
Indian Chambers of Commerce and Industry (FICCI).
</P>
<P>
Hirabayashi said India was sending negative signals by imposing
a 4-percent special additional customs duty. 
