<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: "Grateful for Their Preservation" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton might
have been told the old Chinese saying that "Guilin's landscape is
the best under the Heaven," he was still caught unprepared when
presented with the breathtaking view of grotesque limestone peaks
along the crystal-clear Lijiang River this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The picturesque river, long enjoying the fame of the cream of
Guilin's landscape, personified a perfect Chinese ink and wash as
no other scene in the world will do, agreed Clinton and first lady
Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The 64-km and four-hour excursion on board the boat "Panorama"
took the Clintons through both a fine drizzle and glittering
sunshine, that presented a hazy look of the landscape. The cruise
enabled the Clintons to enjoy the scene featuring uniquely shaped
mountains and meandering river which inspired generations of
Chinese artists and poets, and whose beauty the president found
other words hard to describe except the constant exclamations of
"Great."
</P>
<P>
When the boat sailed by a scenic spot called "Nine Horses Paint
the Mountain," Clinton, with boyish exuberance, began to count the
number of natural formation in the shape of a horse on the cliff.
The guide told Clinton that fable has it that the person who could
make out all the nine "horses" would become the No.1 Scholar in
the highest imperial examination in ancient China, and one who
made out seven will become the No.2. Maybe, it was because of the
relatively high speed of the boat, Clinton said he could only
figure out eight "horses."
</P>
<P>
The boat stopped by a village at the lower reaches of the
river. After being greeted by village head Zhao Jialuo and a score
of school children at the village entrance, the Clintons were
led into the village which has a 492-year history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: "Grateful for Their Preservation"  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Walking down the centuries-old slabstone road, the Clintons
were attracted by one particular house with its painted doors and
windows carved after intricate designs.
</P>
<P>
When Clinton asked when the house was put up and whether other
villagers also have houses with similar doors and windows, Zhao
Jiashuai, owner of the house, replied: "it was put up more than
400 years ago and my family were among the first inhabitants of
the village. Carved beams and painted rafters are part of the
Chinese architectural tradition, which is still being carried
forward in the village today."
</P>
<P>
Very interesting, Clinton commented.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president and the first lady also showed great
interest in the villagers' use of marsh gas generated from pig and
cow dungs as a fuel.
</P>
<P>
"The use of the march gas is an important measure we've taken
to protect the ecological environment along the Lijiang River, and
the residue from the pit may also be used as fertilizer," explained
Li Zhaozhuo, Chairman of the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Regional
People's Government, who was accompanying the Clintons on the
tour.
</P>
<P>
Clinton asked a villager to show him how to use the marsh gas
for cooking and lighting, and he clapped his hands at the sight of
the blue flames dancing on the cooking stove and a lamp. It's very
good to use the marsh gas in rural areas, Clinton remarked.
</P>
<P>
Clinton spoke highly of the beauty of the ancient-style houses
in the village, saying that life in rural China is very
interesting, while he posed for pictures with villagers and
Chairman Li before leaving the village.
</P>
<P>
The Clintons then got on the boat and reached the county town
of Yangshuo at 6:05 p.m. Before he got off the boat, the crew
presented Clinton a piece of exotic stone as a souvenir.
</P>
<P>
"They (Guilin's landscapes) are alive, and we are grateful for
their preservation," Clinton said at the end of the boat ride,
referring to the good preservation of the landscapes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sanctions Against Swiss Banks Threaten Bilateral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Sanctions against Swiss banks by
U.S. cities and states could harm "the good bilateral relations
between Switzerland and the United States", said the Swiss
government Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A group representing some 800 local U.S. finance officials
threatened on Wednesday to impose sanctions against Switzerland's
three biggest banks for their role in handling Holocaust victims'
accounts during World War Two.
</P>
<P>
"These kinds of sanctions are counterproductive, unjustified
and illegal," the Swiss Federal Council (cabinet) said in a
statement. "They constitute a danger to the good bilateral
relations between Switzerland and the United States."
</P>
<P>
While calling on the U.S. government to prevent such sanctions,
the Swiss government said that it would support Swiss companies
that took legal steps against U.S. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Swiss banks involved have indicated that they
may sue U.S. states or cities that will boycott deals with them.
</P>
<P>
The banks could also withdraw the 600 million U.S. dollars
already offered by them to settle their dispute with Holocaust
victims and Jewish groups, who have demanded an amount of 1.5
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"We have not made any decisions yet, of course, but we will now
consider steps... that could go as far as lawsuits," said Credit
Suisse Group's spokesman Ulrich Pfister.
</P>
<P>
"The question of what will happen with the settlement offer
being negotiated is open," Pfister said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Approves Anti-Corruption Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB) on
Thursday approved an anti-corruption policy aimed at reducing the
enormous costs that widespread, systematic corruption exacts from
governments and economies in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
ADB President Mitsuo Sato said in a press release that it was
significant that all members of the Manila-based multilateral
bank's Board of Directors had agreed that corruption has a strong
negative impact on economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
"This policy represents an extremely important extension of our
ongoing work on governance, and the culmination of extensive
dialogue with our member countries," Sato said.
</P>
<P>
The policy paper said that scarce resources are squandered on
uneconomical projects because of their potential to generate
lucrative payoffs, and priority sectors such as education and
health suffer disproportionately.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said it will work with its developing member
governments in attacking corruption on several fronts.
</P>
<P>
The bank said it will push to strengthen public institutions by
making them more efficient, effective, accountable and
transparent.
</P>
<P>
It will press for increased market liberalization and
competition to break up monopolies and increase choices for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
It will also raise anti-corruption issues in country program
development discussions with governments as part of broader talks
on sound development management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan, Maldives Call for Greater SAARC Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Maldivian President Mamoon Abdul
Gayoom left here for home Thursday after a two-day visit to
Pakistan as the outgoing chairman of the South Asian Association
for Regional Cooperation (SAARC).
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Gayoom held official talks with Pakistani
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and they called for a greater role of
SAARC in promoting trade and peace and security in the region.
</P>
<P>
They expressed the hope that the forthcoming SAARC summit in
Colombo, Sri Lanka, late this month will "evolve further
guidelines for achieving the objectives of SAARC and promoting
regional peace and security," said a press release of the Foreign
Office.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed that the peace and security situation in
the region has deteriorated following the nuclear tests by India
and Pakistan in May, the release said.
</P>
<P>
They reiterated the need for the creation of a conducive
environment of harmony and trust in South Asia to accelerate
regional cooperation, the release said.
</P>
<P>
They recalled last year's summit in Male, the Maldives, where
the leaders of the seven-nation forum agreed on a process of
informal political consultations and on recommendations of the
Group of Eminent Persons to carry forward and operationalize this
process to promote peace and stability in the region, the release
said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also decided to maintain regular exchange of
visits at the political and official levels to further enhance and
expand the close, friendly and cooperative relations between their
countries, the release said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
