<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Portuguese JLG Signs Three Notes on Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison
Group (JLG) signed three summaries of talks on Thursday after
winding up its 32nd plenary session here.
</P>
<P>
The summaries include one on the establishment of a Portuguese
language school in Macao, one about the model document on the
transfer of convicted criminals, and one on the foreign business
arbitration law.
</P>
<P>
A joint communique issued Thursday said that both sides have
agreed to continue their efforts for the localization of civil
service, the localization and translation of law and the use of
Chinese as an official language.
</P>
<P>
They have also agreed to step up efforts in consultations on
such issues as the transfer of archives and the nationality issue.
</P>
<P>
In addition, since their last plenary session in March, the two
sides have reached consensus on more than 40 international
conventions that will continue to be applicable to Macao after
1999.
</P>
<P>
Those conventions involve basic rights, labor, international
private law, civil aviation, culture, marine shipping, tourism,
public health, customs, bank and science and technology, according
to the communique.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to put some new topics into the
agenda of the JLG. They include the handover ceremony, the
official status of the Portuguese language, the participation of
the Chinese side in the making of the budget in Macao, and
definition of Macao Special Administrative Region residents and
the rights of abode, the transfer of the legal system and stamp
issuing.
</P>
<P>
Both the Chinese side and the Portuguese side described the
three-day meeting as "friendly and cooperative."
</P>
<P>
The JLG convenes three plenary sessions each year, in Beijing,
Lisbon and Macao respectively. Its next plenary session is
scheduled to start on October 13, 1998 in Lisbon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
