<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Build Two Tourist Complexes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh Parjatan Corporation
(BPC), the country's national tourist organization, will build two
tourist complexes in southeastern Chittagong Hill Tracts, the
national Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha news agency reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government has agreed in principle to set up the complexes
at the Khagrachhari and Bandarban hill districts at a cost of 200
million taka (about 4.35 million U.S. dollars), to tap the natural
resources and speed up development in the region, a BPC official
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the government's plan to boost development in
the hill tracts after it signed a peace treaty with the region's
tribals last December ending the decades-long armed conflict
there.
</P>
<P>
Each of the complexes will have residential rooms for 100
persons, a banquet hall for 300 guests, an international-standard
health club, a shopping arcade, a 100-seat conference room and a
games room.
</P>
<P>
The complexes will also have facilities like hill-top
observation sheds, benches on hill slopes, children's game parks,
water sports facilities, tennis courts and rent-a-car service
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
The fund for the projects is expected to come from the
government's special development fund for the Chittagong Hill
Tracts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
