<HEADLINE> Cyprus Rejects Defense Spending Reduction: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has described as
"unfortunate" a reference in U.N. Resolution 1178 calling for
defense spending cuts on the island.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government rejected such proposals, Foreign
Minister Ioannis Kasoulides said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark Wednesday night upon his return from
Luxembourg, where he attended a working dinner given by the
former British European Union (EU) rotating presidency for the
Foreign Ministers of the 11 candidate countries for EU
membership, Cyprus News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides expressed satisfaction with the content of the two
U.N. resolutions, 1178 and 1179 (1998) on the renewal of the
U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP) and the
Secretary-General's good offices mission on Cyprus, adopted
unanimously by the Security Council earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
He noted that their content has shown that "Turkish efforts to
upgrade the illegal regime in the Turkish-occupied areas of
Cyprus have failed."
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister, however, rejected a call made in the
resolution 1178 for the reduction in defense spending to help
restore confidence between the rival parties on the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriot-dominated north since Turkish
troops landed and took over the northern third of the island in
1974 after a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. Turkey stations
at least 35,000 troops in northern island.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides pointed out that the presence of Turkish occupationtroops on the i
sland is the reason forcing the Greek Cypriot side
to continue bolstering its defense.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the Cypriot government's readiness to
discuss a provision calling for the reduction of Turkish troops
in northern Cyprus and the freeze of armaments by the Greek
Cypriot National Guard, with the objective that a specific
timetable for demilitarization is agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
The proposal for demilitarization, put forward by President
Glafcos Clerides in December 1993, calls for the disbandment of
Greek Cypriot National Guard and Turkish Cypriot armed forces, as
well as the withdrawal of Turkish forces from northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, the weapons should be confiscated and
transferred into the UNFICYP's custody and the money saved
through demilitarization should be deposited into a fund to
benefit the two communities on the island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
