<HEADLINE> Boeing Predicts Rapid Growth for China's Air Transport Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- China's air transport industry
will grow by an average of 9.5 percent annually in the next 20
years, Boeing Commercial Airplane Group predicted in its 1998
market outlook.
</P>
<P>
The forecast growth rate, the highest in the world, almost
doubles the global average figure in the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
Boeing has also predicted that China's airlines will add 1,800
new jetliners in 20 years, with the value of the increased
aircraft totaling 125 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In terms of gross domestic product, the Chinese economy has
grown at an average rate 2.5 times greater than that of North
America and Europe, Boeing said, adding that China will have the
most rapid economic growth rate in the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
On a broader scale, airlines in the Asia-Pacific region will
buy 4,760 jet planes in the next two decades, valued at 427
billion U.S. dollars, Boeing said.
</P>
<P>
Smaller-sized planes -- such as Boeing 717s, Boeing 737s and
Boeing 757s -- will have a dominant market share in the next 20
years, according to the U.S. aircraft manufacturer.  
</P>
