<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The World Bank has granted Egypt 142 million U.S.
dollars in loans for four projects in the 1997-98 fiscal year,
compared with 75 million dollars in 1996-97, a press release
issued Wednesday by the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The loans have been used in financing Egypt's agricultural
projects in the Nile Delta, reducing pollution, encouraging
environmental protection, rehabilitating ports and implementing
health plans.
</P>
<P>
The International Development Agency, an offshoot of the bank,
shared 122 million dollars in the loans with an interest rate of
0.75 percent. The loans will be repaid in 35 years with a 10-year
grace period.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- South Korea's second largest automaker, Daewoo Motor
Co. Ltd, has built an automobile factory in Egypt, which is
believed to be one of the largest in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo shares 60 percent of the 45 million dollars investment
in the Daewoo Motor Egypt, the new joint venture, and the rest is
shouldered by its partner Aboul Fotouh Establishment, one of
Egypt's top five corporations.
</P>
<P>
In two weeks, the factory will produce two models, Lanos 1500
cc and Leganza 2000 cc, with a combined production estimated at
3,500 by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The company will import Daewoo's two other latest models of
1997 and 1998, which are Nubira 1600 cc-16 valve and the smaller
cozy Matiz. Production of pick-up trucks will begin next year.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanian Foreign Minister Jawad Anani said Wednesday
the association agreement signed by Jordan and the European Union
(EU) last November is expected to be ratified by the EU Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The agreement has been referred to the Finance and Economic
Committee of the EU Parliament, Anani told reporters after meeting
the ambassadors of the 15 EU members to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is aimed at promoting EU investment in Jordan
and creating a free trade zone by the two sides by 2010.
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- Japan has agreed to grant the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) 7.5 million dollars to dispose solid waste in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip, the Al Hayat daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to PNA Minister of Local Government Saeb Erekat,
Japan provides the PNA more than 100 million dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
He said that Japan is one of the countries committed to its
pledges to improve the infrastructures of the Palestinian
self-rule areas. 
</P>
