<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Method Promising for Treating Spinal Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli scientist has
developed an innovative treatment of damaged spinal cords,
which has achieved promising results in lab tests on rats, a
report said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This breakthrough could be good news for those paralyzed or
handicapped by injuries to the central nervous system, according
to a report released by the prestigious Weizman Institute of
Science, based in Rehovot, near Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The new treatment was created by Professor Michal Schwartz of
the Neurobiology Department in the institute. Using the new
method, she succeeded in helping rats to regain partial movement
in their hind legs paralyzed by spinal damage.
</P>
<P>
It has long been known that "lower" animals, such as fish, can
repair damaged fibers in their central nervous system -- the
spinal cord and the brain -- and restore lost functions. In
contrast, mammals, including humans, can only repair injuries to
the peripheral nerves, while injuries to the brain or spine leave
them permanently paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
The new approach is based on Schwartz's theory which states
that the loss of this repair ability by the higher animals
occurred in the course of evolution due to a unique relationship
between the central nervous and the immune systems.
</P>
<P>
Schwartz believes this loss was probably dictated by the need
to protect the mammalian brain from the effects of the immune
system. While immune cells normally help to heal damaged tissue,
their access to the brain would disrupt the complex and dynamic
neuronal networks that build up during an individual's lifetime.
</P>
<P>
Generally, when tissue damage occurs, immune cells known as
macrophages swarm to the injured site where they remove damaged
cells and release substances that promote healing. The central
nervous system of mammals or humans, however, is different in this
regard: when damaged, it is not effectively assisted by the
immune system.
</P>
<P>
Schwartz's team discovered that this is because the mammalian
central nervous system has a mechanism that suppresses the
macrophages. As a result, macrophages are recruited to central
nervous system injuries at a lower rate.
</P>
<P>
These findings led to a series of experiments on rats, focusing
on overcoming the limited ability of the damaged central nervous
system to recruit and activate the macrophages. They isolated
macrophages and incubated them in a test tube in the presence of a
damaged peripheral nerve. The macrophages, which received the
distress signals of the damaged peripheral nerve, became activated.
</P>
<P>
The researchers then transplanted the activated macrophages to
the damaged site in the central nervous system of the paralyzed
rat. Then the transplanted macrophages created a growth-inducing
environment around the damaged tissue, enabling the rats to regain
partial motor activity in their previously paralyzed legs.
</P>
<P>
A major innovative aspect of such treatment lies in promoting
the animal's own self-repair mechanism, Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
But she said that at present the results have only been
achieved in tests on rats, and more research work has to be done
before applying the treatment on humans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six ICRC Staff Feared Abducted in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Six staff-members of the
International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC), who have been
missing for a week in eastern Ethiopia, must have been abducted,
said an ICRC official here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The six, five Ethiopian nationals of Somali origin and one
Swiss national, were seen walking with unidentified armed men,
ICRC spokesman Michael Kleiner was quoted by Reuters as saying.
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing new since last Thursday when we lost contact
with the team," Kleiner said. "But we have information from
witnesses who said the six were seen walking with unidentified
armed men to an unknown destination."
</P>
<P>
"This makes us believe they have been abducted."
</P>
<P>
The six were travelling in three vehicles to Degah Bur from
Gode in the ethnic Somali region of Ethiopia when they went
missing. They intended to be there for a training workshop.
</P>
<P>
Degah Bur is about 160 kilometers north of Gode in the Ogaden
region of Ethiopia, close to the border with Somalia. 
