<HEADLINE> 1 Million Lebanese to Face Blackout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 1 million residents in
central Lebanon, including the capital Beirut, will continue to
face power cuts at least six hours a day on a rotating basis in
the coming two months.
</P>
<P>
This was caused by the partial breakdown of two major power
plants in the country, the Voice of the People radio reported here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Zouk plant's third power-generating unit failed in June
while the normal electricity supply of the Hazmieh plant has been
disrupted since Monday due to technical problems.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Hawa, director-general of the Electricite du Liban
(EDL), Lebanon's national electricity company, said that
electricity has been rationed rotatingly among the affected areas
since June.
</P>
<P>
It needs two months to repair the failed units, Hawa said.
</P>
<P>
And the EDL could not assemble power from other parts of the
country because the nationwide transfer network would not be
completed for another 18 months, he said.
</P>
<P>
About 7 percent of Lebanon's 4 million residents suffer daily
electricity cuts currently, according to Hawa. It was only from
1996 that Beirut and its suburbs began to enjoy 24-hour-a-day
power supply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
