<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Hit by Scorching Temperature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The temperature in this economic
center of China today hit a record high for the year, peaking at a
scorching 37.1 degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
The temperature is the same as the highest all last summer.
</P>
<P>
While many places in the Yangtze River Valley and south China
are being ravaged by torrential rains, Shanghai has been suffering
from a heat wave since June 30, when the temperature reached 35.4
degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists here say that the high temperatures are the
result of the sub-tropical high pressure from the west Pacific
Ocean which has blocked cold air from moving southward.
</P>
<P>
Official data indicate there has been relatively little
rainfall in Shanghai since May. Shanghai's precipitation normally
stands at 103.2 millimeters (mm) in May and 178 mm in June. But
this year the two figures are only 79.2 mm and 148 mm,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Experts say they expect high temperatures and little rain in
Shanghai this summer, with the number of days exceeding 35 degrees
Celsius expected to be double that of last year.
</P>
<P>
The weather pattern of high temperatures and little rain should
continue for several days in Shanghai, meteorologists
said. 
</P>
