<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,500-year-old Tomb Found in City of Guilin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A brick tomb with arched ceiling
which dates back 1,500 years has been found in Guilin, a scenic
city in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archeologists said the tomb was located 800 meters from
the site of the prefectural government building in the Southern
Dynasties (420-589), and that the location suggests that the city
had a small population then because tombs were built outside town
in ancient times, while government buildings were always built
downtown, according to the archeologists.
</P>
<P>
The find coincides with historical documents which recorded
that Shi'an Prefecture, present-day Guilin, had seven counties
with a total population of 22,490 during the Southern Dynasties.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
