<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, July 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and his
wife left the scenic city of Guilin this evening for Hong Kong by
the presidential plane to continue his visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and his wife Hillary and some other members of his
official delegation arrived in Guilin from Shanghai at about 10:00
(local time) this morning.
</P>
<P>
In Guilin, Clinton had a discussion with seven Chinese
environmentalists, which lasted about 50 minutes, and delivered a
speech in this regard.
</P>
<P>
"No place in China is more evocative of the beauty of your
country than Guilin," he said, adding that the stunning mountains
along the Lijiang River are alive, and Americans are grateful for
their preservation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president noted that China is making active efforts to
protect the environment, and that the U.S. will step up
cooperation with China in environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
During his visit in China, the two countries have made marked
headway in the cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The president then made a boat excursion on the picturesque
Lijiang River aboard a tourism boat and visited a fishing village
along the bank of the river.
</P>
<P>
At 7:35 p.m., Clinton concluded his visit in the inland areas
of China and left Guilin for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhaozhuo, chairman of the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Regional
People's Government, and his wife; Zhang Wenxue, vice-chairman of
the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Regional People's Government, and
his wife; Chinese Ambassador to the U.S. Li Zhaoxing and his wife,
Vice-Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi and Guilin Mayor Cai Yonglun saw
Clinton off at the airport.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the last leg of Clinton's nine-day five-city state
visit to China. Arriving in the northwest ancient city of Xi'an to
start his visit on June 25, the U.S. president has also visited
Beijing, the Chinese capital, and Shanghai, China's largest
economic and financial center in the east coast.  
