<HEADLINE> China to Import 150 Million U.S. Dollars of Generating Equipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Three Chinese companies this week
signed a contract worth 150 million U.S. dollars with a German
company here to import two 660,000-kw power-generating
boilers and auxiliaries.
</P>
<P>
The two anthracite-fired boilers will be installed in the
Shandong Huaneng Dezhou Power Plant in Dezhou, in east China's
Shandong Province. The generating capacity of the imported
equipment will double the existing capacity of the power plant.
</P>
<P>
The contract was signed by the Deutsche Babcock Energie &AMP;
Umwelttechnik AG, China National Technical Import and Export
Corp., China Huaneng International Trade-Economics Corp. and
Shandong Huaneng Power Development Company.
</P>
<P>
The boilers are equipped with state-of-the-art technology to
meet China's new environmental requirements and are expected to
help China's power industry improve the use and development of the
advenced anthracite-fueled technology.
</P>
<P>
The two imported units are scheduled to become operational in
2002 and in 2003 and are expected to contribute a great deal to
meeting the rapidly growing demand for electricity in the
province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Competitive Edge Improves in High-tech Industry Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- In face of stiff competition in
the global high-tech industry, China boasts a group of high-tech
enterprises with their own intellectual property rights and
technological advantages, said Xu Guanhua, vice minister of the
State Ministry of Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
Xu made the remarks here today at a forum of China's high-tech
industry, adding that China's import and export volume increased
from 12.3 billion U.S. dollars in 1991 to 29.4 billion
U.S. dollars in 1997, of which exports jumped from 2.9 billion
U.S. dollars to 9.6 billion U.S. dollars in the period.
</P>
<P>
And, of China's export of high-tech products, those in the
fields of electronics, telecommunications and biology accounted
for more than 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Xu said that China's high-tech enterprises boast an
ever-increasing competitive edge in the field of information
technology and the scope of those enterprises is also enlarging
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the sales volume of computers made in China
covered more than half of the domestic market, and the
technological capacity of several brand-name computers made in
China could already compete with those of overseas brand-name
computers.
</P>
<P>
Xu said 53 high-tech state development zones set up in the
1991-1992 period across the country have made it more convenient
for China to turn advanced technology into a productive force.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, China's high-tech development zones achieved a gross
industrial output value of 310 billion yuan, and the annual
export of those high-tech zones reached 5.5 billion U.S. dollars,
which means that the annual growth rate of the two indexes over
the past six years has been 91 percent and 92 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Xu said that, although China's high-tech enterprises have made
great achievements, they still occupy an insignificant portion of
the national economy as a whole and, compared with the advanced
nations, China's high-tech enterprises are still lagging behind.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the incremental value of China's high-tech
enterprises accounts for less than 13 percent of the incremental
value of the country's industry, while in advanced nations such as
the United States and Japan, the percentage usually stands around
30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Xu urged China's high-tech enterprises to enroll more talented
young people, so as to give a strong impetus to the development of
China's high-tech enterprises and meet new challenges of the
global market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
