<HEADLINE> President Clinton Arrives in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton flew
into Hong Kong, the last stop of his China visit, Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
The special plane carrying the president and the first lady
from the scenic city of Guilin in southwest China landed at 20:35
local time (12:35 GMT) at the new Hong Kong International Airport,
which was officially opened by Chinese President Jiang Zemin at a
grand ceremony Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) Tung Chee Hwa, his wife Betty Tung and SAR principal
officials greeted President and Mrs. Clinton at the airport.
</P>
<P>
While in Hong Kong, Clinton is scheduled to deliver a speech
and meet local officials, public figures and the press before
leaving for home Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is the first U.S. president to visit the Hong Kong SAR
which was founded on July 1, 1997. He is also the first foreign
head of state to land at the new airport which is due to open for
commercial operation on July 6.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and other senior
officials accompanying the president also arrived by the same
plane.
</P>
<P>
Before coming to Hong Kong, Clinton and his party had visited
northwest China's Xi'an, capital city Beijing, China's biggest
industrial center Shanghai and southwest China's tourist resort
Guilin. 
</P>
