<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana Speeds Up Privatization Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Ghana has embarked on massive
accelerated privatization of its state-owned enterprises, a
report from Accra said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said a number of state-owned firms, including
Gihoc, a pharmaceutical producer, Twifo Oil Palm Holdings and
Barclays Banks of Ghana have been slated for sale in 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the Ghanaian government intends to
sell Gihoc for over 12 million U.S. Dollars. The British Unilever
multi-national group will acquire a 40 percent stock in Twifo
Palm Oil for six million Dollars, while the government's 40
percent holding in Barclays Bank is being sold for 9.5 million
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Apart from foreign and Ghanaian institutional investors who
will bid for stakes in these firms, the report said, individuals
too will have a chance of becoming share-holders via the Initial
Public Offerings of these firms under the auspices of the
regulators and operators of the country's capital market.
</P>
<P>
Three others parastatals, including the Tema Oil Refinery,
Ghana Oil Company and the Cocoa Produce Buying Company, are also
billed for sale in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
This divestiture program, for which a Divestiture
Implementation Committee has been set up, will reduce the size of
the public sector and inject efficiency and qualitative
performance into the enterprises, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It quoted international fund managers as saying that by
mobilizing private sector management and capital, Ghana is on its
way toward overall economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, of the 350 parastatals identified in
mid-1980s by Ghanaian authorities, more than 120 have been either
sold or liquidated in more than 20 transactions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
