<HEADLINE> China, Kazakhstan to Sign Supplementary Border Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- China and Kazakhstan will sign the
second supplement to the Border Demarcation Agreement between the
two countries during President Jiang Zemin's upcoming visit to the
neighboring country, according to Foreign Ministry Spokesman Tang
Guoqiang.
</P>
<P>
The second supplement will comprehensively and thoroughly
resolve border issues and will be of great significance in
promoting friendly bilateral ties between the two countries, said
Tang in reply to a reporter's question at this afternoon's
regular news conference.
</P>
<P>
Tang noted that China and Kazakhstan are friendly neighbors
with a common border of more than 1,700 km, and said that the
Sino-Kazakhstan border was basically solved by the border
agreement China and Kazakhstan signed in 1994 and the initial
supplement to the agreement introduced in 1996. The two documents,
which defined the border alignment in most regions, resulted from
friendly negotiations carried out the spirit of equal
consultations, mutual understanding and accommodations over recent
years.
</P>
<P>
The two sides recently reached a consensus on border alignments
for two remaining regions, and "the agreement to be signed during
President Jiang's visit will be the 'second supplement' to the
original agreement," according to Tang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
