<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Continue to Ride High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket closed
higher for the third straight day Thursday, boosted by strength in
overseas markets overnight and hopes of a resolution to Japan's
economic difficulties Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index ended 43.3 points higher at 2,742.7, a
rise of 1.6 percent, all industrials climbed 78.7 to 4,807.4 and
all resources gained 14.7 to 1,077.9.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said the change in investors' sentiment was palpable
with the market now seemingly much more confident in the future.
</P>
<P>
"There is a lot more optimism out there and we are seeing it
translate into all the stocks now," a Lodge and Partners brokers
said.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said there were a number of reasons for the change in
sentiment including the increased stability in the Australian
dollar, hopes that Japan will resolve its economic woes with a new
package to be delivered Thursday night and the continued resolve
of overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
Overall turnover again topped 1 billion Australian dollars with
366.77 million shares changing hands worth 1.244 billion
Australian dollars (771.28 million U.S. dollars). Rising stocks
swamped falling stocks by 893 to 350.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday, major broking house JB Were and Son recommended that
investors buy into Telstra, valuing the shares in the medium term
at 5.50 Australian dollars each.
</P>
<P>
But insurer AMP again topped the value tables with its 6.5
million shares traded worth 131.1 million Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks were generally higher with Commonwealth the best
performer, up 42 cents, Westpac climbed 17.8 cents, National
Australia climbed 12.2 cents as did ANZ which closed at 11.46
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks defied a 1.80-dollar fall in the price of bullion
to 295.60 U.S. dollars in late Sydney trade to close generally
higher. 
</P>
</TEXT>
