<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Bounces higher, But Short-lived </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar's bounce to
one-month highs proved short-lived Thursday as rumors suggested
Japan would put in place a bridge bank and declare permanent tax
cuts to jump-start its sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar sank to a close of 61.79, half a U.S.
cent lower than its strong finish Wednesday of 62.27.
</P>
<P>
St George Bank manager of foreign exchange trading Stuart Moore
said the market had spent the morning stalling for time, awaiting
the Japanese economic reform announcement.
</P>
<P>
Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party previously announced
tax cuts worth 2 trillion yen (about 7.1 billion U.S. dollars),
but it was seen as a temporary measure.
</P>
<P>
Moore said market participants were cautious and reports later
in the day from Japan suggested the package would not exceed
expectations.
</P>
<P>
Locally, a leading quarterly business survey reported that
Australian business conditions and confidence fell dramatically in
the June quarter as the Asian crisis continued to have a
detrimental effect on the domestic economy.
</P>
<P>
National Australian Bank also said it anticipates further
downside on commodity prices and hence the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
"Based on fundamentals, commodity prices, interest
differentials and the current account deficit, the Australian
dollar is not undervalued at current levels," Oster said.
</P>
<P>
"With falling commodity prices and a worsening current account,
there is little up-side for the Australian dollar during the next
year," Oster said.
</P>
<P>
At the close the Australian dollar was trading at 85.92
Japanese yen from 85.79 and 1.1243 German marks from 1.1251.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
