<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-State-Owned High-Tech Companies Boom in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- China had more than 65,000
non-state-owned high-tech companies with more than three million
employees by the end of 1997, according to the State Ministry of
Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
Vice Minister Xu Guanhua told government leaders and
enterpreneurs attending today's symposium that non-state-owned
companies scored total 1997 revenues of 555.6 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Over 870 companies reported annual output values of at least
100 million yuan each.
</P>
<P>
Some 70 percent of high-tech products manufactured by the
companies were developed internally, said Xu.
</P>
<P>
The companies invested 3.9 percent of their total 1997 revenue,
or some 21.6 billion yuan, in the development of new products. The
percentage for the sector was much higher than that for ordinary
state companies which invested 0.18 percent and for medium- to
large-sized state enterprises which allocated only 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Xu said that non-state-owned high-tech companies will play an
increasingly important role in applying research findings to
production, which will be the focus of China's industrial
development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
