<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Kenyan Coffee Houses Suspended from Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Four leading Kenyan coffee houses
have been indefinitely suspended from the weekly coffee export
auction in a row over representation at the International Coffee
Organization (ICO).
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Thursday quoted senior
industry officials as saying that the dispute revolves around
representation by Kenya's Mild Coffee Traders Association (MCTA)
of trade views in major forums, including the ICO.
</P>
<P>
The four coffee houses were suspended by the MCTA last week
for criticizing the association's performance.
</P>
<P>
"Following your suspension from Mild Coffee Trade Association
membership, the Coffee Payments Marketing Sub-Committee meeting
(held on Monday) suspended your participation in the auctions
with immediate effect...," the Coffee Board of Kenya said in a
letter sent to the four major coffee houses.
</P>
<P>
Leading coffee houses C. Dorman, Cetco and Pati confirmed this
week that they had received such a letter.
</P>
<P>
Coffee officials said Taylor Winch had also received a similar
letter, but traders at the coffee firm said they reserved comment
on the case.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's weekly coffee export auctions are held on Tuesdays.
All the four companies were absent from the auction this week.
However, the four trading houses declined any formal comment on
the matter, said the press report.
</P>
<P>
The row with the MCTA began two months ago when some coffee
houses claimed that their interests were not adequately
represented by the MCTA.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the suspended coffee houses represent about 70
percent of the foreign coffee trade in Kenya. They added that
major international orders could now be delayed by the action.
</P>
<P>
"At auction you obtain the best prices based on bidding. The
less number of bidders available, the limited number of bids and
the limited chances of obtaining maximum profits," one senior
coffee analyst in Nairobi said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is one of the world's leading producers of quality
premium arabica coffees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
