<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 09:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's FM: Ties with Israel Almost Standstill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's Foreign Minister Jawad Anani
has said that Jordanian-Israeli ties are almost at a standstill
and both are at the minimum level of contact and coordination,
according to the official Petra News Agency here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Official contacts between Jordan and Israel are currently
numbered. Most of the contacts are minimized in certain fields
such as water (sharing)," Anani told reporters Wednesday night
after meeting the European Union ambassadors to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The situation can not be blamed on Jordan, but rather is a
result of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's attempts to
ruin every chance of reviving the long-stalled Middle East peace
process, Anani said.
</P>
<P>
In dealing with its relations with most Arab countries, Israel
adopts an intransigent stand and refuses to implement the already
signed peace agreements, thus making the ties, including that with
Jordan, falling down to the low points, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Israel's president (Ezer Weizman) has himself indicated that
Mr. Netanyahu does not want peace, and so, and in the face of
this, we find ourselves forced to accept the minimum offer so
that we can maintain the line of hope," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, becoming the
second Arab country in the region after Egypt to realize peace
with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian official complained that the discussion to
implement items of the peace treaty, such as construction of
airport and sharing water resources, has always been under way,
but few is implemented in real terms.
</P>
<P>
In political aspect, the Jordanian-Israeli ties have never
picked up since they were hurt last year as two Israeli secret
agents were arrested in Amman for attempting to assassinate a
leader of the anti-Israeli organization Hamas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
