<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Enhance Cooperation With China on Environmental Protection: Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States is determined to
strengthen cooperation with China in environmental protection,
visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton said in the picturesque city
today.
</P>
<P>
"Since Chinese civilization first began to express itself
thousands of years ago, its poems and paintings have sung of the
beauty of the land, the air, the water," he said in a speech in a
park in the city.
</P>
<P>
Expressing his admiration of the picturesque scenery of Guilin,
Clinton said: "No place in China is more evocative of the beauty
of your country than Guilin."
</P>
<P>
"The landscapes of Guilin...are alive, and we are grateful for
their preservation," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his speech with the theme of environmental protection,
Clinton said that China is taking impressive steps to protect the
environment so as to secure its future. He cited some examples,
including spreading the use of lead-free gasoline and upgrading
inefficient stoves.
</P>
<P>
He noted that communities and provinces and the national
government are doing more to clean up rivers and that Chinese
scientists are fighting deforestation and soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that Chinese citizens are doing more to promote
public education about the environment, among families and
especially among children.
</P>
<P>
"In October at our summit, President Jiang and I oversaw the
beginning of a joint initiative on clean energy. This week we have
made important new progress," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We ill provide China assistance to monitor air quality. We
will increase our support for programs that support renewable
energy sources to decrease China's dependence on coal," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are helping China develop its coal gasification and working
with the Chinese to make financing available for clean energy
projects through the Export-Import Bank," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Clinton, U.S. Vice President Al Gore and the
Chinese Government launched a forum to coordinate sustainable
development and environmental protection last year.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two countries must work together to protect
the environment.
</P>
<P>
"There is a great deal that we can do together," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has the world's longest meteorological
records, which help people clearly to understand the problem of
global warming.
</P>
<P>
"Without any loss of economic opportunity we can converse
energy much more than we do; we can use clean, as opposed to
dirty, energy sources much more than we do; and we can adopt new
technologies to make the energy we have go further much more than
we do," he said.
</P>
<P>
Before he made the speech, Clinton had a 50-minute discussion
with seven Chinese people on environmental protection in the Hall
of Odd-looking Stones in the Qixing Park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
