<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB to Help Jordan in New Economy-Monitoring System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) will help Jordan
set up a new system to accurately record its economic growth rate,
the Arabic-language daily Al Dustour reported here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Abdul Razzaq Bani Hani, director of the
Research Department of the Planning Ministry, as saying that the
move came as Jordan and the WB are markedly different in their
figures concerning Jordan's economic performance.
</P>
<P>
The WB has recently revealed that Jordan's economic growth was
at most 1 percent and 2.5-3 percent in 1996 and 1997 respectively
as against the 5.2 percent and 5.3 percent released by Jordanian
government, the semi-official Jordan Times reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hani admitted that Jordan's economy declined in the past two
years and thus the WB figures were "more reasonable."
</P>
<P>
Once the new system sets up, Hani said, the government will be
working on providing official economic growth figures on a
quarterly basis.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Foreign Minister Jawad Anani late Wednesday denied
that Jordan was trying to conceal real economic growth indicators,
saying that "We have invited the World Bank (officials) to Jordan
after we found that their economic growth indicators did not tally
with our estimations."
</P>
<P>
WB Vice President Kamal Dervish visited Jordan last week and
discussed the country's economic performance and the 1989-1998
economic reform program sponsored by the International Monetary
Fund and the WB.
</P>
<P>
Local observers said if the WB figures about Jordan's economic
growth prove to be true, the economic reform program will need
huge adjustments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
