<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Inflation Spirals Beyond Target: Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's overall year-on-year
inflation spiraled beyond the official target of five percent in
June mainly due to rising food prices, statistics from the
Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) showed.
</P>
<P>
Overall year-on-year inflation rose to 7.4 percent in June
from 4.6 percent in May, the East African Standard newspaper
Thursday quoted the CBK as saying.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Micah Cheserem has previously said the
bank was targeting inflation at five percent by the end of June,
also the end of the 1997/98 financial year.
</P>
<P>
"The sharp rise in overall inflation in June compared to May
reflects the higher food prices," CBK Chief Economist Maurice
Kanga said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kanga blamed poor infrastructure, especially roads, for the
drastic shift in inflation figures. Kenyan roads are in a weak
state of repair, which has meant that transportation of food
stocks to markets is slow and expensive.
</P>
<P>
Economists said a poor road network and a disruption in rail
service to western Kenya sparked a rise in food transportation
costs.
</P>
<P>
Kanga said the hike in year-on-year inflation was not expected
to be sustained because supplies of food and drink items would
improve in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said underlying inflation, which excludes
food prices, rose to 11.3 percent in June from 10.8 percent in
May.
</P>
<P>
In a weekly update on currency movements, the central bank
said the Shilling had gained to a mean of 59.50 to the Dollar in
the week to June 30.
</P>
<P>
It said the Shilling had gained to 99.26 against the Pound
compared to 99.44 the week before.
</P>
<P>
"The strengthening of the Shilling is mainly due to continued
foreign exchange inflows from tea, coffee and horticulture at a
time when demand for imports is low," the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
The domestic money, the central bank said, tightened further
in the week to June 26 as payments related to the closure of the
fiscal year reduced liquidity in the market.
</P>
<P>
This caused the average interbank borrowing rate to increase
to 29.1 percent from 22.67 percent in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
The average interest rate on the 91-day treasury bill
continued in a downward trend to 25.12 percent in the auction
dated June 29 from 25.40 in the previous auction.
</P>
<P>
The average base lending rate by commercial banks remained
unchanged at 27.97 percent, said the central bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0178 </DOCNO>
