<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise For 7th Straight Day in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed higher in Tokyo
for the seventh consecutive trading day Thursday, boosted once
again by foreign brokerages' heavy buying.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors poured money into low-priced large-capital
issues such as steel and construction companies as Japan
accelerated efforts to resuscitate its economy.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange surged 108.69 points, or 0.66
percent, from Wednesday's close to finish at 16,471.58.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, however, slipped 0.29 point or 0.02 percent
to 1,270.46.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to an estimated 920
million shares from Wednesday's 876.32 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was Thursday's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the Nikkei's current upward trend almost mirrors
that seen in January and February when foreign brokers and
speculators suddenly became huge net buyers of Tokyo stocks.
</P>
<P>
Some traders said institutional investors were encouraged by
reports earlier in the week that the Japanese government may
induce a permanent income tax cut of 2 trillion to 4 trillion yen
(about 14.5 billion dollars to 29.0 billion dollars) next year in
order to boost sagging domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,332 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
surpassed losers 776 to 421, with 95 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
