<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Abiola May Be Released to Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The release of Nigeria's most
prominent politician and business mogul, Moshood Abiola, expected
later Thursday may become the key achievements of U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan in his current visit to the west African
state.
</P>
<P>
Abiola, detained over the annulled June 12, 1993 presidential
polls which he presumably won, is said to be released to Annan,
according to press reports.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived in the country Monday for a four-day visit,
has already held talks with both the head of state, General
Abdulsalam Abubakar and Abiola.
</P>
<P>
This cheery development, according to the Post Express, is
sequel to an agreement reached between the Nigerian government,
Annan and Abiola himself.
</P>
<P>
The detained politician may have already signed an
undertaking, part of which precludes him from traveling out of
the country till the conclusion of the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Abiola may have also agreed to desist from demanding
the mandate resulting from the annulled election five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi also gave similar hint
when he said Wednesday that he would not be surprised that all
sides reach an agreement for the best interest of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, the idea of releasing Abiola is informed
by the need to ensure that agreements reached between the
government and Abiola will not be violated after Abiola regains
freedom.
</P>
<P>
But Abiola would be free to join the presidential race, under
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
This is part of General Abubakar's efforts to resolve the
lingering political crisis which has virtually brought the nation
to its knees these past five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
