<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Are More Internet Savvy: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Widespread Internet use in the
United States has produced more Internet savvy Americans of all
generations, said a new study by MCI Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
An on-line Internet skills assessment revealed that the skill
levels of Americans rose to an average score of 82 percent, up
from 78 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
The second MCI Great American Net Test also found that the
skill levels between men and women are fairly even, with 82
percent for women and 80 percent for men.
</P>
<P>
In terms of age category, the so-called Baby Boomers (age 40 to
60) and the Generation Xers (age 24 to 39) scored the highest, an
average 84 percent.
</P>
<P>
The higher Internet skill level is good news for the country,
MCI said, quoting the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics as saying
that the top three fastest growing occupations are
technology-related. Many other U.S. industries will also seek
employees with new media, Internet-based technology skills.
</P>
<P>
Respondents who access the Internet at home or work are doing
better than those who access the Internet at school.
</P>
<P>
The interactive on-line test covered a three-month period,
beginning from March 30. The test takers had to use the search
technology of the World Wide Web to find answers to nine
questions, including pop culture, world geography, arts and
literature, science and technology, and history.
</P>
<P>
The MCI study also found that most Americans believe the
Internet will still be around in the year 2100.
</P>
<P>
According to MCI, there were less than 300 computers in the
United States being connected to the Internet in 1981 and the
figure rose to 90,000 in 1989. More than 30 million computers may
have been linked to the World Wide Web today and the number could
double by the year 2000, the telecommunications company said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
