<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prarastatin Reduces Risks of Repeat Heart Attack: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A study released Wednesday said
pravastatin, the cholesterol-lowering drug, can reduce risks of
repeat cardiac events among women who, with average cholesterol
levels, have already had heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
The study, published in the July issue of the Journal of the
American College of Cardiology, was conducted by a team of
researchers led by Sandra Lewis of Portland Cardiovascular
Institute in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
The researchers studied a group of 576 postmenopausal women who
had heart attacks 3 to 20 months earlier. All of them had total
cholesterol levels lower than 240 milligrams per deciliter (mg/dl)
of blood, and low-density lipoprotein (also called "bad"
cholesterol) levels between 115 and 174 mg/dl, the investigators
reported.
</P>
<P>
The researchers randomly divided the women into two different
groups. One group took 40 milligrams of pravastatin daily for 5
years. The other group took a placebo pill daily for 5 years.
</P>
<P>
After just one year, the women taking pravastatin saw their
risks of coronary events drop more than 50 percent, with the risks
of fatal and nonfatal heart attacks dropping 55 percent while risk
of stroke dropping by 56 percent, the researchers found.
</P>
<P>
"Women with a heart attack show strong, early reductions in
recurrent coronary events during therapy with pravastatin, despite
having average cholesterol levels before treatment," the authors
conclude. "Treatment will prevent an extensive range of subsequent
cardiovascular events." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
