<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania, Mozambique to Build Bridge over Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania and Mozambique plan
to build a bridge across the Ruvuma River on their common border
but the two countries have yet to reach an agreement on the
specific construction site.
</P>
<P>
The two governments have formed a joint technical committee
that will coordinate the construction of the bridge, John
Magufuri, the Deputy Minister of Works of Tanzania, has said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the National Assembly in the city of Dodoma
Wednesday, Magufuri said suggestions have been made to construct
ferries or bridges over the river.
</P>
<P>
The official was answering questions put by members of
parliament who wanted to know the government's plans to build a
unity bridge across the river, according to a report by The
Guardian paper Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania and Mozambique share a border of some 800 kilometers
along the Ruvuma River without a bridge. People on both sides
have to use boats to cross the border.
</P>
<P>
Magufuri told parliament that facilities for the building of
the bridge have arrived in Tanzania, adding that the donor will
transport the facilities from Ngara District in Kagera Region to
the construction site in Ruvuma Region.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the British government has agreed to donate
a bailey bridge.
</P>
<P>
"The major problem, which is stalling construction of the
bridge, is Mozambique's reluctance to build at the suggested
Mitomoni area," the paper quoted Magufuri as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the Tanzanian government is still contacting the
Mozambican government on where to build the bridge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
