<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Copper Price Hits 10-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Copper futures fell to the
lowest points on Wednesday since 1988 on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, according to news reaching here late in the day.
</P>
<P>
Copper for July delivery fell 1.35 cents to 72 cents a pound,
the lowest since the current contract began trading in July 1988
and reaching a 10-year low. The active September contract fell 1.2
cents to 72.60 cents a pound.
</P>
<P>
Copper is heavy tied to the construction industry, with uses in
electrical devices, plumbing and wiring. Industry analysts believe
that the latest fall of copper prices was caused by three factors.
</P>
<P>
First, there are signs of a cooling U.S. economy. The Commerce
Department reported that U.S. construction spending fell by an
unexpected 1.5 percent in May, the first decline in six month and
the steepest drop since January 1994. The National Association of
Purchasing Management's index also foreshadowed an economic
contraction, with manufacturing activity falling to 49.6 in June
from 51.4 in May.
</P>
<P>
Second, there seems to be no quick recovery in Japan despite
new proposals to stimulate that economy. Japan is the
second-largest copper consuming nation behind the United States.
</P>
<P>
Third, The London Metal Exchange reported that the inventories
of copper in its warehouses rose for the first time in several
sessions by 1,250 metric tons to 248,900 metric tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Reform Promotes Rising Grain Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in Chongqing have
expressed delight with the recent rise in grain prices which
reversed consistent declines recorded during the previous five
months.
</P>
<P>
The upturn has been attributed, at least in part, to the success
of the ongoing reform of the grain marketing sector which urges
state grain purchasing enterprises to adhere to government-set
purchasing prices.
</P>
<P>
Government policies stipulate that grain must be purchased at
subsidized prices when market prices fall below designated levels.
</P>
<P>
Local pricing authorities report that grain price rose by an
average one to two jiao (8.3 jiao equals 10 U.S. cents), with the
highest jump hitting 3.5 jiao in Chongqing, one of four Chinese
municipalities administered directly by the central
government. Price rises were also recorded for vegetables and pork.
</P>
<P>
The fact that some grain purchasing companies previously
lowered prices to remain competitive caused prices of grain,
vegetables, pork and other types of farm produce to fall by a wide
margin. Falling prices reduced the municipality's price level by
five percent for the first five months of this year and adversely
affected the city's normal economic growth pattern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Orders Cut in Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has directed
all oil producing companies in the country to cut down on their
production to reflect its commitment of further reduction in
output by 100,000 barrels per day (bpd).
</P>
<P>
The directive issued Tuesday took effect as from Wednesday,
the Daily Times reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria reduced its crude oil production last April by 125,000
bpd and further agreed to cut output by 100,000 bpd in line with
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) decision
last week to boost oil prices in the international market.
</P>
<P>
The national daily quoted economic analysis as saying that the
100,000 bpd reduction in output translated to a drop of about 306
million U.S. Dollars in the 1998 projected revenue.
</P>
<P>
The government was expecting a revenue of 9.8 billion Dollars
from oil export this year.
</P>
<P>
With the fresh cut, Nigeria's oil production stands at 2.033
million bpd, while companies have made plans to expand output.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
