<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Stresses Music Education in Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Education, Sport and
Culture Minister Gabriel Machinga said the government has high
regard for music education in both primary and secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing 31 primary and high school teachers doing
special studies in music at the Zimbabwe Ethnomusicology College
of Music in Harare, the Herald reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
''The government takes music education as a global enterprise
which is deeply rooted in the history of the human race and in
hearts and minds of the people,'' the minister said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Machinga said the promotion of Zimbabwean cultural values in
schools would not be successful if music was not taught in
schools.
</P>
<P>
Music, he stressed, played a major economic role in the number
of sectors including the hotel, recording, broadcasting, tourist
and advertizing industries.
</P>
<P>
He said the curriculum development unit was now working on an
''0'' level music syllabus to be brainstormed by the national
panel in September this year. 
