<HEADLINE> Kenyan Bank Workers Plan to Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan bank workers are planing to
go on strike at the end of this month, threatening to paralyze
banking operations across this east African country.
</P>
<P>
Their unions, the Kenya Union of Commercial Food and Allied
Workers (KUCFAW) and the All Banks Shopstewards Committee, have
agreed to give the government a 21-day strike notice starting
Friday, national media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bank workers are grousing over a tax recently imposed on
low-interest staff loans. They also want the recently introduced
fringe benefit tax removed, said the report.
</P>
<P>
"The union's drums of war are ready, the hammer is ready to
hit and our secretary-general has released the arms to you with
which to fight for what is yours," said Jackson Mukolwe, KUCFAW's
assistant secretary-general in charge of bank issues.
</P>
<P>
"We have no choice but to formalize the strike notice to the
Minister for Labor," said the union's deputy secretary general
Olilo Nyumba.
</P>
<P>
Pressure for industrial action mounted when bankers froze
loans to staff following the introduction of the fringe benefit
tax earlier last month.
</P>
<P>
KUCFAW Chairman Rasugu Ogamba said it was wrong for the
government to snatch from bankers a benefit which they have
enjoyed over a hundred years.
</P>
<P>
He asked Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae to consult bankers to
evade tampering with policies likely to cause chaos in the
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
