<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMS-GT Members Urged to Collectively Promote Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Member states of the
Indonesia- Malaysia-Singapore Growth Triangle (IMS-GT) have been
urged to adopt a pro-active role in investment and trade
facilitation to ensure continued tourism investment.
</P>
<P>
Regional cooperation in tourism has been acknowledged as one of
the strategies that should be fully capitalized upon in order to
gain from rich long-haul markets, Malaysian Culture, Arts and
Tourism Minister Sabbaruddin Chik said when opening an
international conference on tourism development in the IMS-GT in
Johor Baharu, southern Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
This required governments of member states to adopt a
pro-active role in investment and trade facilitation to ensure
continued tourism investment and trade cross flows within the
IMS-GT region, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the tourism industry has been acknowledged as a
fast-track project of the growth triangle because the industry
was relatively matured and represented an important source of
foreign exchange and employment opportunities for the local
population.
</P>
<P>
"We should brace ourselves from now to adapt to the changing
scenario of the tourism industry of the future. The next
millennium would pose a greater challenge to the industry with
stiffer competition, declining profit margins and the development
of other new tourism markets and products," he was quoted by
Malaysia's news agency Bernama as saying.
</P>
<P>
These challenges could only be met by enhancing the
comparative and competitive advantages especially in the aspect of
quality of services which has been the strength and edge of the
industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the private sector of the IMS-GT to venture into
collaborative promotional programs and joint tour packages that
would enable the industry to offer greater variety of events and
destinations to potential tourists.
</P>
<P>
The current regional economic crisis and local currency
depreciation required the respective governments to identify a
strategic approach to expedite recovery from the slump, he said.
</P>
<P>
The crisis should not be considered as a burden but rather an
opportunity to intensify efforts towards enhancing tourism
promotion and marketing activities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Collectively, the tourism sector contributed a significant gain
to the regional economy, with an equivalent of 4.4 percent of the
gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, ASEAN countries -- Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam --
received 31.7 million tourists with total receipts of 31 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is Malaysia's third revenue earner, after manufacturing
and palm oil, he said, adding when the tourism policy was drafted
in the early '90s, a target of 12.5 million tourist arrivals was
set with projected revenue of 8.3 billion ringgit (about 2 billion
dollars at current rate) by 2000, but this target was achieved
much earlier, in 1994 when tourism brought in 8.9 billion ringgit
(about 2.2 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The one-day conference was attended by tour operators from
Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0222 </DOCNO>
