<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, July 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on Wednesday declared
six flood-stricken West Virginia counties as federal disaster
areas, making federal funding and low-interest loans available to
residents and businesses.
</P>
<P>
The counties declared disaster areas are Braxton, Gilmer,
Jackson, Kanawha, Roane and Wood, the U.S. media reported.
</P>
<P>
Floods since the weekend rendered 129,000 customers without
electrical service, mostly in the central parts of the state.
(US-Flood)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Three men were arrested in Texas on Wednesday on
charges of threatening to use biological weapons against federal
agents.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Bureau of Investigation agents charged Johnnie
Wise, 72, Jack Abbott Grebe Jr., 43, and Oliver Dean Emigh, 63,
with conspiracy to use "weapons of mass destruction," an
Associated Press report said. (US-Bio-Weapons-Arrest)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Albanian Foreign Minister Paskal Milo said Wednesday
that the ethnic Albanians and the Serbian authorities will have
their last chance for talks on ending the Kosovo conflict next
week.
</P>
<P>
Milo said that his government was still determined to work with
the international community and push all the parties involved in
the conflict to the negotiation table. (Albania-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- An Italian appeal court ruled on Wednesday that
convicted Nazi war criminal Erich Priebke, who is now 86, is to
remain under house arrest in an apartment in Rome.
</P>
<P>
Judge Renato Teresi of the Rome Court of Cassation turned down
a defense request for Priebke's release from house detention and
ruled that the former SS captain would stay under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
Priebke and fellow Nazi officer Karl Hass were sentenced on
March 7 to life imprisonment by a Rome Military Appeal Court for
their part in the Fosse Ardeatine massacre on March 24, 1944.
Italy-Nazi War Criminal. (Italy-Nazi War Criminal) 
</P>
