<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hewlett-Packard Chooses AMD Chip for New PCs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Hewlett-Packard, one of the
giant computer-makers, has chosen a new AMD chip in two new models
of personal computers, AMD (Advanced Micro Devices) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The chip is AMD's new K6-2 processor equipped with advanced
multimedia and three dimensional capabilities, called the 3DNow
technology, which analysts have said is more advanced than Intel
Corp.'s current multimedia technology known as MMX.
</P>
<P>
The models are two of Hewlett-Packard's just-announced Pavilion
personal computers, running at speeds of 300 megahertz and 333
megahertz, AMD added.
</P>
<P>
Hewlett-Packard's new Pavilion line features six models. Among
the rest four models, three are using Intel's Pentium II
processors and one uses Intel's lower-cost Celeron chip for the
"basic" PC market.
</P>
<P>
The six Pavilion models, all with Microsoft's Windows 98
pre-installed, are Internet-ready. Retail prices will range from
999 dollars to 2,049 dollars, depending on the configuration,
without the monitor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
