<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Sees No Cash for Kenya in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenya must meet its promises on
taxes and corruption before a suspended International Monetary
Fund (IMF) loan can start again, and payments are unlikely in
1998.
</P>
<P>
However, Evangelos Calamitsis, head of the IMF African
Department, said there is a chance that the payments on the
three-year credit could resume in the financial year to end on
June 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Before we actually sign on the dotted line, we may need to
see some action... It would be very tight to resume lending this
calendar year," Calamitsis was quoted by Thursday's media as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"But everybody has said they hope that something can happen
before the end of the fiscal year," he said in Washington
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The IMF halted its lending program to Kenya on July 31 last
year, citing poor governance and corruption.
</P>
<P>
The IMF demands the probe on the Goldenberg corruption case be
speeded up, an independent anti-corruption agency be set up, the
independence of Kenya Revenue Authority be guaranteed and
problems facing the energy sector be tackled with.
</P>
<P>
"Some movements have been made on the last three, but the
first point (the Goldenberg case) is still outstanding," said
Calamitsis.
</P>
<P>
Businessman Kamlesh Pattni, his Goldenberg company and three
former senior government officials have pleaded not guilty to
charges of stealing billions of Shillings from Kenya's Treasury
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
IMF officials said their next mission to Kenya was tentatively
expected in September, but that would not yet be the forum to
decide whether to recommend that the IMF restart payments on the
205-million-U.S.-Dollar loan.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's economy grew just 2.3 percent in 1997, failing to keep
up with the population growth of about 2.5 percent in 1998, the
Central Bank says, adding, it expects a pick-up in growth this
financial year.
</P>
<P>
Since the cut of IMF aid loans, the economy in this east
African country has been severely hit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
