<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Completes Work on Solar Pilot Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- With the completion of work on the
country's 62-kw photovoltaic pilot project in the northeast
Narsingdi district, more Bangladeshis living in remote areas will
soon be able to use electricity in their daily life.
</P>
<P>
The successful implementation of the pilot project, which was
now at the final stage of implementation, would help the nation
enter into an arena of renewable energy, said a report reaching
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The work on the pilot project, covering isolated islands of 29
square kilometers with about 8.500 households, started in January
1994 and ended in December 1997, but its commercial energization
only started in August 1996.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 solar energy consumers would be provided with
electricity under the program, Abdul Halim Mollah, chief engineer
of the Rural Electrification Board (REB) responsible for
implementing the project, was quoted as saying. And under the
expansion program, about 50,000 consumers would be provided with
selectivity in the district, he added.
</P>
<P>
In view of its successful implementation, the Energy Ministry
and the REB was considering expansion of the project by bringing
areas of different districts under it, and donor agencies had
shown interest in funding more similar projects, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has deputized a local firm to conduct a
socio-economic survey on the financial viability of the project,
based on which the bank would provide 5 million U.S. dollars from
its Global Environment Fund for the project.
</P>
<P>
Kishoregonj and Natore, 88 kilometers northeast and 172
kilometers northwest of here respectively, has been identified by
experts as prospective areas where the World Bank-financed project
could be implemented, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Roughly five out of every six people of the country's 127
million population have no access to electricity consumption,
particularly in the remote areas, where consumer density is low,
and which are unlikely to be covered by the national grid network
in the near future.
</P>
<P>
In this context, experts said, renewable energy is a viable
option for the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
