<HEADLINE> Stone Carvings In Chinese Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Staff at Beijing's Museum of Stone
Carvings report that there are more than 20,000 stone carvings in
the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
They have come up with this figure after an 11-year study in
Beijing's 18 districts and counties and in the Badaling and Ming
Tombs zone (where 13 Ming Dynasty emperors are buried).
</P>
<P>
The stone carvings consist of steles, carvings, statues,
pagodas, epitaphs, decorated archways, and stones used for
mounting a horse, and they cover a long period of time from the
Stone Age to now, and are mostly found in urban areas, museums and
temples.
</P>
<P>
Contacts with western countries and exchanges with ethnic
groups are reflected in the carvings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
