<HEADLINE> Milk, Dairy Products in Short Supply in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's milk and dairy products
are in short supply because 20,000 dairy cows were lost in recent
droughts.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the shortage, producers could only supply half
the potential local and foreign markets, prompting high imports
of dairy products, The Herald daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The National Association of Dairy Farmers (NADF) said
Wednesday high input costs of stock-feed and veterinary products
had cast a dark cloud over the market as producer prices remained
well below the expectations of the farmers.
</P>
<P>
At least 75 percent of dairy producers' input costs go toward
feeding the cows. Prices of stock-feed rose by about 60 percent
at the beginning of the year and milk production subsequently
dropped on average from about 500,000 liters a day to 390,000
liters.
</P>
<P>
NADF Chairman Dave Conolly said the failure by farmers to meet
the demand by local processors had forced wholesalers to import
dairy products, mainly from South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
