<HEADLINE> Chinese Securities Dealers Concentrated In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has one of China's two
stock markets, six local securities companies and three trust and
investment companies.
</P>
<P>
Huaxia and Nanfang, two national securities dealers, have
branches in the city, where there are 463 securities outlets, 272
of them from other parts of the country. The city also has 31
offices of overseas securities dealers.
</P>
<P>
The technology and equipment used by these dealers have made
the stock trading more efficient and have enabled investors to
monitor the action and do business via computer and phone.
</P>
<P>
Local dealers have helped investors understand the ins and outs
of the securities business and laws and regulations, and, as
competition has grown, they've adopted various ways to promote
their business, sending staff members out onto the street to drum
up business or by sending customers on holiday or by giving
lectures or consultation.
</P>
<P>
A city official in charge of the industry says that local
securities dealers have made some progress in standardization,
marketing, and professional training, but a few have broken the
law by opening illegal outlets. 
</P>
