<HEADLINE> AL: Arabs Oppose Aggression Against Fellow States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL)
Secretary-General Esmat Abdel-Meguid said Wednesday that the
22-member Arab group is opposed to aggression on any Arab country,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark when commenting on a missile attack on an
Iraqi radar site by a U.S. fighter jet Tuesday, upon his returning
here from a visit to Syria.
</P>
<P>
But the AL chief said that so far he has not received any full
details or information about the incident.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. F-16 fighter fired a missile at an Iraqi radar station
on claims that Iraq radar locked on British patrol planes on a
routine mission over Iraq's southern no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Denied Tuesday that it targeted any of the British patrol
planes and called the U.S. missile attack another proof of
Washington's hostile policy.
</P>
<P>
The attack followed a lull in the U.N.-Iraqi standoff over
U.N. inspections of Baghdad's weapons of mass destruction, which
involved a buildup of U.S. and British forces in the Gulf earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is pressing for an end to U.N. sanctions imposed after its
invasion of Kuwait in 1990. The U.S.-led multinational allied
forces drove Iraq out of Kuwait in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid was in Syrian capital Damascus to take part in
three-day meetings of the Arab tourism ministers. He held talks
with Syria's senior officials as part of the effort to unify the
Arab stance on the Middle East peace process, which has been
deadlocked for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
His talks there underlined the importance of holding an Arab
summit to tackle the challenges stemming from Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's hardline policy and the worsening
situation in the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
