<HEADLINE> Chinese Bank Agreement For Export Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Export and Import Bank of China
(EximBank) and Industrial and Commercial Bank of China (ICBC)
signed an agent bank agreement today to increase support for
machinery exports.
</P>
<P>
The EximBank will give the ICBC the power of agent to handle
export business through its nationwide branches. The ICBC has so
far handled about 3.3 billion yuan (398 million US dollars) worth
of this business already, accounting for more than a third of
EximBank's total.
</P>
<P>
EximBank is a Beijing-based policy-oriented bank that was
founded in 1994 to finance electronics, machinery, and other
capital goods exports, and provided financial support for 9
percent of exports of these products in 1997. It has no
subsidiaries in other parts of the country and has signed similar
agreements with a number of other banks like the Bank of China,
the Agricultural Bank of China, the Bank of Communications, and
the Minsheng Banking Corp.
</P>
<P>
To further increase exports, the bank plans to increase its
credit line by 60 percent this year over 1997 to 24.3 billion yuan
(2.9 billion US dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
