<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Boosting Provincial Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The private sector of southwest
China's Sichuan Province is becoming the most active component of
the local economy as well as a new economic growth area.
</P>
<P>
The sector, with 1.6 million household-run firms employing 2.5
million people, had 42.8 billion yuan in output value last year,
accounting for 19 percent of the province's gross domestic product
(GDP).
</P>
<P>
And it also turned in 3.8 billion yuan in taxes, making up 22
percent of local revenues, according to the provincial Bureau for
Industry and Commerce.
</P>
<P>
The province adopted measures to encourage private businesses
to take on multiple forms, to participate in the effort to merge,
purchase, operate on contracts, and buy into state-owned and
collective enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Now, an increasing number of private firms are ending the
single-product practice; instead, they are turning to diversified
market economies and performance, undergoing a shift from
extensive operations to intensive ones, and from small production
to the modern enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan has set up 15 experimental zones for private sector
development. Statistics show that the zones registered an average
increase of more than 30 percent in output value and pre-tax
profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Painful Reform in Thailand: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand began to float the baht
against the U.S. dollar on July 2 last year, unleashing an
economic nightmare which soon spread to Southeast Asia and other
parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
The past year witnessed painful efforts Thailand has made to
tide over the economic woes which are gripping the country with an
intensity that the country has never seen in decades.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai on Tuesday tried to play down the
anniversary of the baht float, making it clear that ramifications
of the sharp devaluation of the baht are still present and painful
and will continue to be so at least until next year.
</P>
<P>
From 25-26 baht to the U.S. dollar during the 13-year currency
peg system, the Thai currency collapsed to 57 baht a dollar in
mid-January this year before recovering to 38-39 baht for the most
part of March and May. Since then it has weakened again, moving
beyond the 40-baht mark in June, dragged down by the steep plunge
of the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
At the close of Asian spot trading on Tuesday, the dollar stood
at 42.2 baht, a drop of 38.7 percent since the currency peg was
abandoned.
</P>
<P>
Despite mounting skepticism and growing pains, Thailand has
reasons to be proud of its performance in dealing with the crisis.
At least, Thailand, unlike Indonesia, has enjoyed a relatively
stable political situation since the coalition government led by
Chuan took office late last year. Such political stability enables
the government to concentrate on implementing its reform policies.
</P>
<P>
As required by the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Thailand
embarked on the bumpy road of reform one year ago, adopting a
restrictive, albeit subsequently more cautions fiscal and monetary
policy to reduce the demand pressure and restore confidence in the
currency. Moreover, Thailand took a major step in carrying out an
institutional reform, including the Bank of Thailand
restructuring, a banking system overhaul, state enterprise
privatization and legal system modification to clear the way for
an economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
After "swallowing" the IMF-prescribed "bitter pills," Thailand
has made gains and suffered losses at the same time.
</P>
<P>
The once-fragile financial system has been strengthened since
the government closed down 56 poorly-run financial firms and took
over seven debt-ridden banking institutions. A tight monetary
system and high interest rates have also restrained financial
institutions from issuing non-performing loans.
</P>
<P>
The baht has been stabilized within the 40-42 limit, living to
the government's expectation of preventing the currency from
drastic falls in the first half of 1998. Also, improvement in the
financial sector has helped restore foreign investment confidence,
drawing back part of the foreign capital that had flowed out of
the country.
</P>
<P>
The government's performance has pleased the IMF, which
prescribed remedies for Thailand's ailing economy. Successful
cooperation between the two sides has led to the conclusion of
four letters of intent, through which batches of IMF aid is
provided to the country. Such aid has eased the economic hardships
to a certain extent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
