<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Attract Tourists in Open Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is starting preparations to
attract more tourists to the country in the forthcoming open
season from October to April in an effort to develop its tourism
industry.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of Myanmar's Tourism Development Management
Committee here Wednesday, Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt, first
secretary of the State Peace and Development Council, urged
remedial measures to prepare for the best conditions in the
tourist season after the country received a low number of visitors
in the past years, the official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said the public suffered great losses since the number of
tourists was not up to expectations.
</P>
<P>
A Visit Myanmar Year campaign was launched at the end of 1996
to get more tourists to the country.
</P>
<P>
A great deal of local and foreign investors established hotels,
motels and inns and travel and tourism services with a huge amount
of capital for the tourist year, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, a total of 251,500 tourists
visited Myanmar in the 1996-97 fiscal year and 190,580 in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
Up to the end of 1997, the number of private-run hotels and
inns stood at 548, that of tourism agencies 622, passenger
transport services 1,620 and tourist guides 2,763, the statistics
showed.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in the country's hotels and tourism sector
exceeded 1 billion U.S. dollars in March, the end of the 1997-98
fiscal year, in more than 40 related projects out of the total
foreign investment of 7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is rich in tourist attractions such as recreation
sites, scenic beaches, natural forest resorts, sites rich in
cultural heritage, traditions and customs of nationalities and
other places of interest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
