<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Decide on Accord With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
actively considering signing the Status of Forces Agreement (SOFA)
with the United States and will take a decision in this regard
soon, State Minister for Foreign Affairs Abul Hasan Chowdhury
said.
</P>
<P>
"Signing of the SOFA is under consideration. The draft is still
under study," a report in Thursday's edition of The Daily Star
newspaper quoted the state minister as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to take a decision. We have neither said yes nor
no," a high official with the Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Dhaka is expected to proceed with the signing of the agreement
after the Foreign and Defense Ministries receive clarification
from the U.S. side, the report said, quoting diplomatic sources.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would provide legal cover to the movement of U.S.
Armed Forces personnel, military hardware and supplies in times of
emergency in the South Asian country.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad said Bangladesh
would "go ahead with our own thinking," denying allegations that
India was pressurizing Bangladesh not to sign the SOFA. Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina paid a brief visit to India in mid-June,
reportedly to seek India's consent to the proposed agreement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a spokesman of the U.S. Embassy here said on
Wednesday that negotiations on the SOFA "are still going on"
between Bangladesh and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We are expecting a positive response from the Bangladesh
government in respect of signing the Status of Forces Agreement
between the government of Bangladesh and the U.S.A.," U.S.
Ambassador to Bangladesh John C. Holzman said on Tuesday in
Sylhet, Northwest Bangladesh, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
