<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Soldiers Unveil New Eyewitness on WWII Bio-Warfare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- World War II Japanese soldiers
unveiled here Wednesday new eyewitness testimony of war atrocities
during the Nanking Massacre and Unit 731's human biological
experimentation.
</P>
<P>
"About 1,000 Chinese people were used as a material for
living-body test and had their blood out while they were still
alive" in the then Japanese army's Bacteriology Research Center
which was built in a small village in northeastern China in 1933,
said Ogawa Takemitsu, former Hokushi army surgeon, at a press
conference at the National Press Club in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
Takemitsu is among members of the Japanese National Association
for Reparations to Victims of Biological Warfare, who were touring
North America to seek support for cases on behalf of victims of
Japan's World War II biological warfare Unit 731.
</P>
<P>
"In 1935, 731 army was established by an order of Emperor
Hirohito in Pingfang, Harbin. It was called Department of
Epidemic Prevention," Takemitsu said.
</P>
<P>
He said as a student of the Manshu Medical School he
experienced events with 731 army after 1939. It was said that the
experiment of typhus vaccine was on monkeys in bacteriological
course, but later "I heard that monkeys were Chinese people and
they vivisected them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Takemitsu said he participated in the bacteriological warfare
in 1940 at Xinjing as a student of Manshu Medical School and
worked for prevention of epidemic as there was an outbreak of
plague near a pet's hospital. But "later it became clear that
Ishii unit (731) brought in the plague to that pet's hospital."
</P>
<P>
"In 1940 at Ningbo, in 1941 at Jinhua, in 1942 at Changde,
Ishii unit operated bacteriological warfare," he said. "Commander
Ishii Shiro proclaimed that 731 army had already established the
method of bacteriological warfare with plague to the General Staff
Office in 1941."
</P>
<P>
Two eyewitness statements were read at the press conference for
Shiro Azuma, a Japanese soldier who participated in the Tape of
Nanking in 1937, and Yoshio Shinozuka, who committed atrocities as
part of Unit 731. The two men planned to participate in person,
but were denied entry to the U.S. because of their war crimes.
</P>
<P>
In his testimony, Shinozuka said, Unit 731 carried out
experiments on human beings in China under a name of Water
Sanitation.
</P>
<P>
"I participated in the mass production of pathogenic germs from
July 1939 onwards and in the beginning of August, delivered the
same to Jiang Jun Xiao of the frontlines of Nomonhan," He said.
And the germs were flung into Rivers.
</P>
<P>
"The group I belonged to also carried out experimentation on
and dissection of living human beings. I personally participated
in the testing of the potency of plague germs for one year from
the end of 1942," He said.
</P>
<P>
"We infected five Chinese men with plague germs. Not only did
we watch them suffer from horrible pain, but also watched them die
an agonizing death," Shinozuka said.
</P>
<P>
On the Rape of Nanjing, Shino Azuma said, "our tactics was to
invade and plunder. We looked for food. If women in hide were
found, we rape them."
</P>
<P>
Also at the press conference, Diana Zuckerman with the
Institute for Women's Policy Research and Gregory Rodriquez,
biological experiment victim's son, urged the U.S. government and
the Japanese government to make public the records on biological
warfare during the World War II.
</P>
<P>
Dong Woo Lee Hahm, Washington Coalition for Comfort Women
Issues, and Melvin Rosen, survivor of Death March and Japanese
prison camp, also denounced Japanese criminal activities during
the War and demanded the Japanese government to apology for the
atrocities committed by the Japanese aggressors before and during
World War II. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
