<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Sticks to Barring Additional Incentives for Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Foreign companies in Bulgaria have no
grounds to claim that they are not familiar with the Bulgarian
laws, as Bulgarian regulations are analogous to those in Western
Europe, a Bulgarian official told a news conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement made by Nikolai Pavlov, chairman of the
Commission for the Protection of Competition (CPC), was prompted
by the insistence of Shell-Bulgaria to revoke an amendment to the
law on the protection of competition under which foreign companies
operating on Bulgarian territory do not have the right to promote
their products through games of chance.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian parliament adopted the amendment a month ago.
</P>
<P>
Dimiter Kyumyurdjiev, a CPC member, said the legislations of EU
countries, the U.S. and Japan all bar giving additional incentives
in the form of prizes which exceed by far the price of the
commodity or service offered by the respective company.
</P>
<P>
He stated that such provisions have also been adopted by
Germany, France, the Netherlands and others, where companies like
Shell, Danone, Procter &AMP; Gamble and American Tobacco are seated.
</P>
<P>
These companies are fussing in the media against the Bulgarian
legislation, ignoring the fact that it is in conformity with
Western ones, Kyumyurdjiev added.
</P>
<P>
Shell company said although this provision was in line with
European legislation, the social and economic conditions in
Bulgaria are not suitable to apply European standards.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of other foreign companies raised similar
demands as Shell's. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
