<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Asian Financial Crisis to Persist (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More and more economists have predicted recently that the Asian
economy is likely to decline by 0.1 to 1 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The persistence of the Asian crisis should also be attributed
to the Japanese economic recession and a weak yen in particular.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that Japan's GDP fell by an annualized
5.3 percent in the first quarter, the second consecutive quarter
of decline.
</P>
<P>
The economic recession in Japan is reducing demand for Asian
products, hurting exports of countries in the region. In April,
Japan's imports from members of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations fell by 26 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
But a weak yen is a more serious disaster for other Asian
countries. The cheaper Japanese exports resulting from a weaker
yen, which tumbled nearly to 147 against the U.S. dollar on June
15, have threatened exports growth in Thailand, Malaysia,
Indonesia and South Korea. These countries had hoped that their
currency slump in the past year could boost their own exports and
fuel recovery.
</P>
<P>
In addition, many analysts fear that a tumbling yen would cut
Japanese bank loans to other Asian countries, which are badly in
need of funds to reactivate their economies.
</P>
<P>
Japanese bank loans outstanding to Asia stood at 249 billion
U.S. dollars at the end of 1997, a third of total foreign lending
to the region. As most of the loans are denominated in dollars,
the further depreciation of the yen will mean more losses to
Japanese banks. Accordingly, Japanese banks would reduce their
loans to Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, Asian currencies enjoyed a respite Wednesday, on
the eve of the first anniversary of the start of the regional
financial crisis, as the yen stayed firm on positive expectations
for the Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
The yen surged to above 138 to the dollar from 140.45 on the
previous day, partly due to the tax cut reports and also because
of continued cautious optimism about a plan to clean up the
Japanese banking system.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese newspaper Yomiuri Shimbun reported Wednesday that
the ruling Liberal Democratic Party had decided to implement
permanent income and residence tax cuts and a plan would be
announced before the July 12 upper house elections.
</P>
<P>
But many analysts adopted a wait-and-see attitude toward the
yen's trend.
</P>
<P>
Another important cause of the persisting crisis is the
strengthening of economic globalization, under which an isolated
political and economic incident in a country would bring about a
chain of negative effects on the regional, or even the world
economy.
</P>
<P>
Since its outbreak a year ago, the crisis has gone from bad to
worse owing to the social unrest in Thailand, South Korea and
Indonesia and the nuclear tests in India and Pakistan, further
delaying the regional economic recovery process.
</P>
<P>
Economists predicted that since a lot of economic and political
uncertainties still remain in Asia, the financial crisis may
continue to hurt the region in the months ahead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
