<HEADLINE> Improving Traffic Situation In Southwestern Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- At a cost of approximately 500
million yuan (60 million US dollars), Kunming, the capital of
southwest China's Yunnan Province, recently completed four road
projects that largely improved the city's traffic conditions.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, Kunming had some 900 km of streets and
roads in a nine-sq-km area, or 6.6 square meters per capita.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Kunming will get more than 2 billion yuan (240
million US dollars) to complete a major traffic network this year
for the 1999 World Horticulture Exposition there, scheduled from
May 1 to October 31, next year. It will be the first large global
exposition China ever hosts. As many as eight to 10 million
visitors from both at home and 60 countries and 30 international
organizations worldwide are expected at the exposition.
</P>
<P>
Kunming is expected to build or rebuild 49 roads in urban areas
for this purpose. 
</P>
