<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Asian Financial Crisis to Persist (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- One year after its eruption, the
Asian currency crisis is showing no signs of abating and an Asian
turnaround may still take some time as the crisis seems deepening.
</P>
<P>
On July 2, 1997, the floating of the Thai baht triggered a
currency turmoil first in Southeast Asia and then in South Korea.
The whole Asian region and even the rest of the world have felt
the severe impact of the crisis since then.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, the affected countries have done their
best to ease the crisis by undertaking economic adjustments and
financial reforms. The International Monetary Fund, the World Bank
and the Asian Development Bank have provided billions of dollars
to bail out the economies of Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
However, the crisis seems persisting and even deepening with
continuous declines of currencies, slowdown of economic growth,
rising inflation, closures of banks and companies and massive
layoffs in the crisis-hit nations and other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Some Asian currencies, in the meantime, are dropping to the
level of January when the crisis entered a deteriorating phase.
</P>
<P>
Why is the one-year-old crisis lingering on?
</P>
<P>
Economists believe that as the Asian economy is facing a
possible recession this year, the worsening situation may postpone
economic reforms in the region and as a result, the current crisis
may last longer than most people have expected.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, the economies of Thailand,
Indonesia, Malaysia and South Korea registered negative growth
while the Singapore economy showed signs of a possible recession.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, considered the least-affected by the
crisis, the gross domestic product (GDP) achieved a mere
1.7-percent growth in the first quarter, much lower than the 5.1
percent registered a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In April, the Philippines' export increased only by 9.8
percent, compared with the average 23 percent in the first three
months of the year, and its unemployment rate rose to 13 percent,
the highest in seven years.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that with the full-blown impact of the crisis on
their economies, Asian countries may experience the most difficult
time in two decades this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Snub-Nosed Monkeys Discovered In Southwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese zoologists have found more
than 1,000 snub-nosed monkeys in China's southwest Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
These Yunnan snub-nosed monkeys were found in the Samagong
forest area in Weixi County, over 3,500 meters above sea
level.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan snub-nosed monkeys were previously thought to mainly
live in the Baimang (Whiteness) Snow Mountain state nature
reserve, over 3,800 meters above sea level and more than 200 km
away from Samagong forest area, which is in the northwestern part
of the province.
</P>
<P>
The Yunnan snub-nosed monkey is a rare species that has been
included into the No. 1 Category of widelife listed under state
protection in China.
</P>
<P>
The monkeys substitute on a diet of fruits and leaves. They
are snow white when they are young and their backs turn black as
they grow.
</P>
<P>
The Samagong Forest is a primeval area of some 50,000 hectares
of land between the upper reaches of the Jinsha and Lancang
rivers, where there are many rare animals and plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
