<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Second Largest Copper Mine Discovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Investment Company of Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region has decided to join three other businesses
in building China's second largest copper mine, after the Dexing
Copper Mine in Jiangxi Province, at a cost of 800 million yuan (96
million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The ore at the Ashele Copper Mine, in Xinjiang's Habahe County,
was first discovered in the late 1980s. In the intervening years,
44.38 million tons of ore that contained more than a million tons
of copper and large amounts of zinc, gold, silver, and pyrite have
been dug out.
</P>
<P>
According to a new plan, the mine will be designed for a daily
production of 3,000 tons of ores, capable of producing annually
100,000 tons of copper concentrate, 20,000 tons of zinc
concentrate, and 870,000 tons of sulphur concentrate.
</P>
<P>
Drilling and pit projects have been completed and China's
second largest mine is taking shape.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts predict that China will need 1.3 million tons
of copper annually, but domestic supplies can account for
two-thirds of that amount, so the new copper mine is expected to
resolve this problem to some extent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
