<HEADLINE> Austria Takes Over Reins of Changing EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Austria took over the rotating
presidency of the European Union (EU) from Britain on Wednesday
and vowed to push forward the European integration process and
internal and external reforms.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian government held a special meeting on Wednesday
morning and adopted a working scheme for promoting the union
during Austria's six-month tenure.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor Viktor Klima and Vice Chancellor and Foreign
Minister Wolfgang Schuessel said that European integration, EU
enlargement and structural reform, the smooth issuance of the
euro, and lowering unemployment would be top of the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Both said Austria was confident of fulfilling the tasks and was
well prepared for taking up the EU presidency.
</P>
<P>
Klima said that Austria must devote itself in the cause.
</P>
<P>
Schuessel said, "It will be a genuine working presidency,
hopefully very professional, intelligent and well thought
through. I know we have back-breaking work to do on some issues."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday afternoon, a music-and-dance spectacle was held on
the Heldenplatz (Hero's Square) in front of the imperial Hofburg
Palace to celebrate Austria's presidency. European Commission
President Jacques Santer and other senior EU officials attended.
</P>
<P>
Austria joined the EU in January 1995. It will hand over the
presidency to Germany on January 1, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
