<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Cut Maximum Weight of Rice Sack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Labor and Social Welfare
Ministry has approved a regulation to cut the maximum weight of a
rice sack from 100 to 55 kilograms in an effort to entice Thais to
take jobs to be vacated by foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper The Bangkok Post Thursday quoted the ministry as
saying the measure is in line with international standards.
</P>
<P>
The approval came after 400 rice millers decided to suspend
operations and halt paddy purchases from Thursday in protest
against a ban on alien labor from July 10. They say Thais are
unwilling to take jobs in the industry, which is short of an
estimated 200,000 laborers.
</P>
<P>
Under the regulation, a male worker can carry a sack of no more
than 55 kilograms and a female 30 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation of foreign workers is part of the Thai
government's efforts to alleviate the mounting problem of domestic
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
According to the Labor Ministry, the number of jobless people
in Thailand has reached 2 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
