<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Facsimile Market in U.S. Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Americans continue to look to
fax machines for sending documents despite the growing popularity
of e-mail, according to a California-based market analysis firm.
</P>
<P>
The country's facsimile revenue is projected to reach three
billion U.S. dollars in 1998, up 17.7 percent from 1997 revenue of
2.6 billion dollars, reported Dataquest, part of the Gartner Group.
</P>
<P>
Dataquest said in a new report that the number of facsimile
compatible devices sold would grow from 5.5 million units in 1998
to 7.5 million units by 2002.
</P>
<P>
Personal or low-end products, which include multifunctional and
single-function fax machines, grew 81 percent from 1.6 million
units in 1996 to 2.9 million 1997, according to Dataquest. This
represented a 44 percent increase in terms of revenue.
</P>
<P>
Dataquest predicts continued robust growth in the low-end
market as color-printing and laser multifunctional products ride
the uptake of PCs in homes, home offices and small businesses.
</P>
<P>
The workgroup market including mid-range and high-end products
experienced no growth from 1996 to 1997, with sales in both years
of 525,000 units. Dataquest predicted that sales of these products
would generate 5.7 billion dollars in cumulative hardware sales
revenue from 1998 to 2002, and 17 billion dollars if adding
service and supply revenues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
