<HEADLINE> Indonesia Launches Massive Rice Market Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
launched a massive market operation to help millions of poor
families across the country deal with the economic crisis, leading
local newspapers reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The operation, which was announced Wednesday by chief of the
National Logistics Agency (Bulog), Beddu Amang, is aimed at poor
people most vulnerable to food shortages.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, the government will provide medium quality
rice at 1,000 rupiah per kilogram to families whose earnings are
insufficient to bring them out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
The rice prices in the market is 2,500 to 3,200 rupiah per
kilogram.
</P>
<P>
Amang said that on the first stage, the operation will cover
179,000 poor families in Jakarta, capital of Indonesia, and the
its surrounding areas such as Bogor, Tangerang and Bakasi.
</P>
<P>
In the second stage, he said, this will be extended to cover
1.6 million poor families in 53 districts in 15 provinces and in
the third stage, it will cover a total of 7.35 million needy
families in this country of more than 200 million people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Food and Horticulture Minister AM Saefuddin said a
special team will be set up to run the market operation.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged drought and deteriorating economic conditions
over the past year have combined to increase the number of people
deemed as vulnerable to food shortages.  
</P>
</TEXT>
