<HEADLINE> Clinton Arrives in Southwest Chinese City of Guilin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, July 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton arrived
in this scenic city in southwest China by the presidential plane
from Shanghai this morning on the fourth leg of his nine-day state
visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Arriving at the Guilin Liangjiang Airport at 10:15 a.m. local
time (02:15 GMT), the U.S. president and Mrs. Clinton were warmly
greeted by Zhang Wenxue, vice-chairman of the Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, and his wife, and Guilin Mayor Cai Yonglun and
his wife.
</P>
<P>
Two children presented bouquets of flowers to the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador to the U.S. Li Zhaoxing and his wife, and
Vice-Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi also greeted the presidential
couple at the airport.
</P>
<P>
Among those accompanying President Clinton to Guilin are U.S.
Ambassador to China James Sasser and his wife, and Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
After their arrival here, President Clinton and his official
delegation went to Qixing (Seven Stars) Park for a forum on
environmental protection, where the president will make a speech.
</P>
<P>
The Clintons will then cruise the scenic Lijiang River, and
visit Xingping Village at the lower reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
Being one of the most famous tourist attractions in china,
Guilin is known for its unique limestone scenery.
</P>
<P>
Upon the Clintons' departure from Shanghai, the third stop
their his China trip, earlier this morning, they were seen off by
Shanghai Mayor Xu Kuangdi and his wife, and Vice-Mayor Zhou Muyao
at the airport.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president had a tight schedule during his 60-hour stay
in Shanghai, China's industrial and financial hub, where he had
panel discussions with people of various walks, attended a live
talk show on local radio, and visited a local family and a variety
of cultural and financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated in Shanghai that the U.S. does not support
independence for Taiwan, or "one China, one Taiwan," or "two
Chinas," and does not believe Taiwan should be a member in any
organization for which statehood is a requirement.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton is scheduled to conclude his tour of Guilin
and leave for Hong Kong later today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
