<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation in Thailand Reaches 10.7 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Inflation in Thailand in June
remained in double digits for the third consecutive month, rising
10.7 percent year-on-year, the newspaper The Nation reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The rate was 10.2 percent in May and 10.1 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Commerce Ministry attributed the bigger rise in June
to a 13.6-percent increase in food and beverage prices and an
8.8-percent price rise in the non-food sector.
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Price Index for the first six months of this year
was 9.7 percent, with prices up 11.8 percent in the food sector
and 8.4 percent for non-food items.
</P>
<P>
Though prices have gone up to reflect rising production costs,
most manufacturers have been making a good effort to hold the line
on prices, Karun Kittisataporn, director-general of the Business
Economics Department, said.
</P>
<P>
According to the department, the wholesale price index in June
rose by 20.7 percent over the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
Karun acknowledged that the inflation rate over the past few
months was the highest since 1981, when a fuel crisis pushed the
rate to 11.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said his department expected that the rate for the year
would be below the 10.5-percent figure projected by the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Karun forecast a drop in the inflation rate in August as prices
and costs stabilized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
