<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Basic Facts About HK New Airport at Chek Lap Kok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
will officiate at a grand opening of the new Hong Kong
International Airport at Chek Lap Kok this morning. Here are some
basic facts about the new airport.
</P>
<P>
The airport is located 25 kilometers west of Hong Kong's
Central business district.
</P>
<P>
Covering an area of 1,248 hectares, the new airport is almost
four times the size of the existing airport at Kai Tak. The
airport platform was formed by leveling the tiny islands of Chek
Lap Kok and Lam Chau and reclaiming land from the sea.
</P>
<P>
When it opens for commercial operation on July 6, the first of
its two 3,800-meter-long runways will be in service. The new
airport will operate round the clock without the night-time flight
restrictions imposed at the existing airport at Kai Tak.
</P>
<P>
The new airport will be able to handle 35 million passengers
and 3 million tons of cargo annually compared with the 28.3
million passengers and 1.79 million tons of cargo that passed
through Kai Tak in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The second runway will be commissioned by the end of 1998. The
airport will be developed in phases and ultimately is expected to
handle 87 million passengers and 9 million tons of cargo a year.
</P>
<P>
The new Hong Kong International Airport is one of the ten
infrastructure projects known collectively as the Airport Core
Program. These developments include 34 kilometers of expressways
and tunnels, a high-speed rail link that will carry passengers
between the Central business district on Hong Kong Island and the
new airport in just 23 minutes, a third-crossing harbor tunnel and
a new town development. The total estimated cost of the entire
program is 155.3 billion HK dollars (19.9 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Y-shaped airport passenger terminal, covering a floor space
of 515,000 square meters upon opening and 550,000 square meters by
the end of 1998, ranks among the world's largest terminals. Signs
posting throughout the terminal are clear and simple.
</P>
<P>
There are 38 bridge-served gates for wide-bodied aircraft (48
by the end of 1998) and 27 hard-stand gates. Accessibility to the
bridge-served gates will be facilitated by a driverless shuttle
train and moving walkways.
</P>
<P>
Departing passengers should take less than three minutes to
check in at nearly 300 desks. From each of these desks, as well as
16 over-sized luggage check-in counters, luggage will move
smoothly on its way through a sophisticated luggage handling and
screening system, so the highest levels of security will be
maintained. It should take no more than 30 minutes to complete
check-in and immigration formalities to board aircraft.
</P>
<P>
With 12 reclaim carousels handling almost 20,000 pieces of
luggage an hour, passengers may claim their luggage quickly after
entering the arrivals area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
