<HEADLINE> Coastal City Cultivating Marine Fishery Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Dandong City, the northeastern
starting point of China's coastline, has taken steps to cultivate
its marine fishery resources.
</P>
<P>
Dandong, which sits at the estuary of the Yalu River into the
Yellow Sea, has a coast of 93.3 kilometers and its offshore waters
are home to more than 70 kinds of fish. It is one of China's
well-known marine fishing ground.
</P>
<P>
A decline of the marine fishery resources in the offshore areas
has been reported as a result of over-fishing. Beginning in 1986,
Dandong has been sending fry into the offshore areas of the Yellow
Sea, including 4.57 billion head of baby prawns, 8.25 million of
young chum salmon and 750 million jellyfish fry in an effort to
restore fishing resources.
</P>
<P>
The effort has shown economic results. The city has harvested
1,600 tons of prawns and farmers have earned 55 million yuan from
prawn fishing in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Last year, output value of sea-based aquatic products reached
2.4 billion yuan, five times the 1985 level and contributed 15.8
percent of the city's gross domestic product for 1997, according
to local sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
