<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's GDP to Decline: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's gross domestic product
(GDP) is predicted to decline by more than 10 percent this year
due to the slowing down of the country's economy and the lack of
confidence in the business sector, a government official said.
</P>
<P>
"But the decline in economic activities is believed to stop as
economic programs are carried out while confidence of economic
players is restored," Coordinating Minister of Economy, Finance
and Industry Ginandjar Kartasasmita told a limited cabinet meeting
on economic, financial and industrial affairs here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the meeting, Information Minister Yunus Yosfiah
told reporters that Ginandjar predicted that the inflation rate in
the 1998 fiscal year will reach 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
The prediction is based on the rate during the first semester
of this year, Yunus was quoted by the local press Thursday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
From January to June, the inflation rate in the country was
expected to be 46.55 percent and the biggest contributors to the
inflation during June were food and clothing.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet meeting said the government would take special
steps to maintain the 1998-99 budget at normal level, according to
Yunus.
</P>
<P>
He said the budget deficit could not be continually maintained
although it is acceptable to the country which is going through
difficult times.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the ratio of the budget deficit to the GDP will be
decreasing in the 1999-2000 fiscal year," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
