<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nazi War Criminal to Stay Under House Arrest in Rome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 1 (Xinhua) -- An Italian appeal court ruled on
Wednesday that convicted Nazi war criminal Erich Priebke, who is
now 86, is to remain under house arrest in an apartment in Rome.
</P>
<P>
Judge Renato Teresi of the Rome Court of Cassation turned down
a defense request for Priebke's release from house detention and
ruled that the former SS captain would stay under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
Priebke and fellow Nazi officer Karl Hass were sentenced on
March 7 to life imprisonment by a Rome Military Appeal Court for
their part in the Fosse Ardeatine massacre on March 24, 1944.
</P>
<P>
In October last year, seven months after his re-trial for the
massacre, the worst atrocity in Italy during the World War II,
Priebke was transferred from a Franciscan monastery in Frascati
outside Rome to a Rome military hospital to serve out the
remaining months of his sentence.
</P>
<P>
He was then moved to an apartment in Rome. But because of
complaints from neighboring residents, he was later transferred to
an undisclosed location.
</P>
<P>
Priebke was one of the Nazi officers who were responsible for
rounding up and shooting 335 Italian civilian men and boys at the
Ardeatine Caves in reprisal for a partisan bomb that killed 33
German soldiers in downtown Rome. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
