<HEADLINE> 87-Year-Old Chinese Artist Hosts Painting Exhibition in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Cheng Ji, an 87-year-old Chinese
painter, recently returned to China after residing in the United
States for 51 years to serve as host of an exhibition in the
Shanghai Museum.
</P>
<P>
The one-month exhibition displays 63 watercolor paintings
created by Cheng since 1941. The artwork features a combination of
traditional Chinese painting skills with western painting methods.
</P>
<P>
Born in 1912 in Wuxi, a city in east China's Jiangsu Province,
Cheng started to study art of watercolor painting in Shanghai when
he was 14 years old.
</P>
<P>
Cheng went to the United States in 1947 and continued his work
which has led to a worldwide reputation.
</P>
<P>
He has won 50 international fine-art prizes and his paintings
have been included in collections at numerous art museums in the
United State. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Gets World Bank Grant for Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has received a grant of
15 million U.S. dollars from the World Bank to convert primary
schools into junior schools, Education Ministry sources said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The conversion is being done on the recommendations of the
Presidential Task Force on General Education Reforms. It will seek
to ensure that education is compulsory for children in the 5 to 14
age group.
</P>
<P>
The sources said this will help rationalize and uplift the more
disadvantaged segment of the country's school system in the
initial phase of restructuring education.
</P>
<P>
A school mapping process is already in progress and a
comprehensive survey to identify and collect information on
schools will also be undertaken soon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the National Institute of Education is developing a
framework to introduce a system of school-based management. This
concerns the functions to be delegated to principals in teacher
recruitment and deployment, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
