<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Families Buy More Durable Consumers Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The average ownership of household
durable consumer goods has increased considerably in this
financial and economic center of China.
</P>
<P>
The per capita annual disposal income of Shanghai residents
exceeded 8,400 yuan last year, 3.4 times the 1991 figure,
according to an official survey. In another measurement, the
increase has averaged 22.6 percent each year during the period.
</P>
<P>
Most families with rising incomes have turned to high-grade
durable goods for spending. The survey shows that for every 100
Shanghai households there are an average 119 color TVs and 102
refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, household ownership of air conditioners has
surged, from an average of 0.4 units in 1991 to 62 last year. The
ownership of video recorders, washing machines and water heaters
is also steadily rising.
</P>
<P>
Luxury durables such as pianos and personal computers have also
made their way into ordinary Shanghai households. Another survey
of more than 1,300 students indicates that 10 percent of the
student families have purchased computers, with another 50 percent
planning to buy one.
</P>
<P>
Many households in Shanghai have begun replacing durable goods
bought in the 1980s with more advanced ones with a higher level of
technical content. They now prefer large-screen color TVs and
super-large, freon-free refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts say that Shanghai residents have become more
rational in their decisions to purchase durable goods and the
average household ownership of durables, especially large-screen
color TVs and personal computers, is expected to rise steadily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
