<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Foreign Exchange Reserves Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The foreign exchange reserves of
Bank Indonesia (BI) increased by 7.6 million U.S. dollars last
week, the local press Thursday quoted a BI press statement as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's foreign exchange reserves jumped to 14.6095
billion dollars on June 26 from 14.6019 billion dollars on June
19, the first rise during the last three weeks.
</P>
<P>
BI said the increase in the reserves mainly came from oil and
gas exports.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, BI's claim on the Indonesian Bank Restructuring
Agency (IBRA) slightly declined to 132.34 trillion rupiah (about
13.2 billion dollars) on June 26 from 133.28 trillion rupiah on
June 19.
</P>
<P>
The decline was because banks under the supervision of IBRA had
settled part of their liquidity credit injected by the central
bank, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
BI has been injecting credit liquidity to troubled banks while
IBRA has the responsibility for recovering the loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
