<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Encourages Establishment of State Health Townships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- China has encouraged its 18,000
counties and townships nationwide to improve the quality of their
environment and the health level of their residents, according to
a recent national conference on the establishment of state health
townships.
</P>
<P>
During the conference held in Suzhou, a city in east China's
Jiangsu Province, the first group of such state health townships
includes Tangqiao Township in Jiangsu, and Xin'an and Shanlan
townships, both in south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Liquan County in Xianyang City of northwest China's Shaanxi
Province has been named China's first "state health county."
</P>
<P>
Residents of these townships and county have good natural
environments and are generally healthy, one official said.
</P>
<P>
He added that, about eight years ago, more than 600 Chinese
cities joined the contest to establish state health cities and
some 29 cities nationwide have been named as "state health cities"
and some 100 cities have been named as "provincial level health
cities."
</P>
<P>
The official emphasized that the environmental quality of
townships is of great importance as the dominant part of Chinese
peasants living in small-size townships.
</P>
<P>
The conference called on township governments across the
country to strengthen health education for peasants and to improve
air quality, water quality, road conditions, waste disposal and
the hygienic situation of toilets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
