<DOCNO> XIE19980702.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government to Push Tax Amnesty Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The cash-strapped Philippine
government is pushing for a tax amnesty program to raise at least
20 billion pesos (500 million U.S. dollars) in revenues to help
reduce its projected 40-billion-peso (1 billion dollars) budget
deficit in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The amnesty forms part of a multi-point tax program for which
legislative support will be sought by the administration when the
congress reopens on July 27, the newspaper The Philippine Journal
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The tax measures are intended to help erase the hefty deficit
in the budget by yearend triggered mainly by the financial crisis
and the decreasing tax collection, Finance Secretary Edgardo
Espiritu was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said the tax amnesty plan, which has been opposed by
the International Monetary Fund, would hardly hit the low-income
group and other marginalized sectors.
</P>
<P>
The plan is aimed at going after the idle rich, the affluent
members of the underground economy by encouraging them to come out
into the open with hidden and unused assets, he explained.
</P>
<P>
The plan is presently being worked out by the Bureau of
Internal Revenue and former Senator Edgardo Angara for
presentation to the congress when it reconvenes.
</P>
<P>
Measures are also being drawn up to encourage those who refuse
to pay taxes to the government or those who hide or understate
their assets to comply with existing tax regulations.
</P>
<P>
The government's financial position has been deteriorating this
year due to the prolonged financial crisis which began to plague
the country in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
The government, which has enjoyed budget surplus yearly during
the past four years, posted a 15.4-billion-peso (390 million
dollars) budget deficit for the first five months of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
