<HEADLINE> Rare Relics Unearthed from 2,400-year-old Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A square bronze mirror with four
dragons in openwork, gilded bronze weapons and a painted bronze
cooking vessel with lid have been unearthed from 2,400-year-old
tombs in Xichuan County in central China's Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
The relics were among some 200 pieces of bronzeware unearthed
from 15 tombs believed to belong to nobles of the Chu State in the
early Warring States Period (475-221 BC).
</P>
<P>
Chinese archeologists say that the find will contribute to the
study of the Chu culture. 
</P>
