<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rich Urged to Help Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- China's rich people have been urged
to contribute to the country's help-the-poor drive, which aims to
eliminate poverty in the country by the year 2000, said today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
This was the theme of an international forum on the role of the
private sector in poverty alleviation through social efforts and
balanced regional development, which opened in Beijing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The symposium was sponsored by the United Nations Center for
Regional Development, the Development Research Center of China's
State Council and the China Brilliant Cause Promotional Commission.
</P>
<P>
There are at present 50 million people in China with an annual
income below 630 yuan (79.5 US dollars) which means they cannot
afford sufficient food and clothing.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank counts those who earn less than one dollar per
day as poor, and one third of China's 900 million farmers fall
into this category, said You Hongbing, deputy secretary-general
of the Foundation for Underdeveloped Regions in China.
</P>
<P>
The forum encourages enterprises' participation in regional
development and poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
People are getting richer. Savings deposits have increased from
21 billion yuan (2.52 billion US dollars) in 1978 to the current
5,000 billion yuan (600 billion US dollars). But is is not a
balanced growth, You said.
</P>
<P>
Two-thirds of the money comes from urban residents, who make up
25 percent of the population. And one-third of rural deposits
comes from farmers living in coastal regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
