<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Philippine Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Philippine newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Despite objections from the International Monetary Fund,
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu is pushing for a tax amnesty
program to help raise from 20 billion to 30 billion pesos (750
million U.S. dollars) in revenues for the cash-starved
administration of President Joseph Estrada.
</P>
<P>
Manila Bulletin:
</P>
<P>
-- President Joseph Estrada on Wednesday declared all-out war
on crime syndicates, particularly drug lords who, he warned, "will
be hunted to extinction during my administration."
</P>
<P>
Today:
</P>
<P>
-- the new administration will push for the immediate release
of some 600 million dollars in "budgetary support" loans from the
World Bank to help cover the projected 37-billion-peso (925
million dollars) deficit in the national budget this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
