<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Australian newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian:
</P>
<P>
-- Australian Prime Minister John Howard resolved the native
title issue Wednesday night in a personal victory that caps five
years of intense and often divisive battles over aboriginal land
claims.
</P>
<P>
-- Net immigration would be reduced to zero under One Nation
Party's immigration policy unveiled Wednesday and refugees would
be forced to return to their homeland within five years.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald:
</P>
<P>
-- Australia will not go to a double-dissolution race election
in the next few months after Prime Minister John Howard Wednesday
abandoned his opposition to three of the four sticking points on
his amendment bill on native title and accepted a compromise on
the right to negotiate over pastoral leases.
</P>
<P>
The Age:
</P>
<P>
-- The state government of Victoria Wednesday threatened to
pull the plug on its 3 billion U.S. dollar gas privatization and
reform program, blaming regulatory uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review:
</P>
<P>
-- Australian banks face a new wave of bad debts from corporate
borrowers in their push for growth, with the country's leading
bank the National Australia Bank the most exposed and Westpac the
least at risk, a new survey has found.
</P>
<P>
-- Australia should not underestimate the value of maintaining
geopolitical stability between Washington and Beijing and U.S.
President Clinton's China visit is a precondition for a return to
Asia's economic prosperity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
