<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Players Enter Labor Waiting Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The third NBA players lockout in
four years went into effect early today.
</P>
<P>
Owners imposed the lockout after they were unable to reach a
new collective bargaining agreement with the players association
in the past three months. It means teams cannot transact any
business involving players.
</P>
<P>
They can't sign free agents, make trades, conduct training
camps or sign players selected in the draft last week. Michael
Olowokandi, selected No. 1 by the Clippers, returned to his home
in England to wait out the dispute.
</P>
<P>
They can, however, sign coaches, meaning Chicago, Clippers and
Denver can fill their vacancies.
</P>
<P>
League and union representatives have met nine times since
April 1 but made no progress. Future talks haven't been scheduled,
and none are expected until mid-July after union player
representatives meet in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
The NBA players union is considering staging a series of
exhibition games this summer to generate revenue for its members
during the lockout.
</P>
<P>
"We've gotten a lot of offers over a period of time," union
first vice president Charles Smith said. "We have explored some
opportunities. It's someting you have to look at it if this is an
additional revenue steam for players."
</P>
<P>
Union executive director Billy Hunter has said that when
polled, 90 percent of union membership said they were prepared to
stay out the entire season and would not need financial assistance.
</P>
<P>
This is the third time players have been locked out in the past
four years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
