<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopes Cease-Fire Before Serb Pullback in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration has
eased its demand for an immediate withdrawal of Serb forces in
Kosovo, stressing there should be a cease-fire first before the
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration is holding to the demands for a
withdrawal of the Serb forces, State Department spokesman James
Rubin said Wednesday, adding the American diplomats are trying to
arrange a cease-fire first.
</P>
<P>
That may ensure that ethnic Albanian fighters do not seize the
opportunity of a troop withdrawal to rush in to fill the vacuum
and gain more territory in Kosovo, Rubin added.
</P>
<P>
"As a practical matter, we don't expect to see that kind of
pullback in the absence of a cease-fire. That doesn't mean we
wouldn't prefer to see it without a cease-fire, but as a practical
matter that, in our view, is the most likely sequence," he added.
</P>
<P>
The shift was the second major move by the administration in
the past week to try to revitalize its diplomatic approach to the
conflict between Serbs and ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Rubin said the dialogue between the ethnic Albanian
leadership and Belgrade should be open to the armed Albanian
insurgents who had been denounced previously as acting like
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
The contacts are expected to intensify next week when U.S.
mediator Robert Gelbard goes to Europe for a meeting with German,
British, French, Russian and Italian diplomats in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
Gelbard and other American diplomats are proposing a seat at
the table for the Kosovo Liberation Army alongside Ibrahim Rugova,
the pacifist moderate who many ethnic Albanians look to as their
leader.
</P>
<P>
However, Rubin reiterated that the Serbs are primarily to blame
for the bloodshed in the southern province and that the United
States has the authority to use force to halt the fighting if
diplomacy fails. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
