<HEADLINE> Boeing Deliveries Up in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Boeing delivered 139 airplanes
in the second quarter this year, up from 108 in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Altogether the Seattle-based manufacturer has delivered 247
airplanes for the first half of 1998, slightly short of its goal
of 250.
</P>
<P>
The company said Wednesday that a growing number of planes is
being completed but then put in storage. Financial problems for
Asian airlines have led to storage of 19 completed airplanes, up
from eight at the beginning of the year. Boeing expects to deliver
these jets by year-end, some possibly to different customers than
those ordering them.
</P>
<P>
Boeing still plans to deliver 550 jetliners this year, but it
will have to continue increasing its delivery pace through the
rest of the year to meet that target. Over the past six months the
company has been taking measures to streamline and accelerate
production.
</P>
<P>
"Our main issues now are production efficiencies, getting ready
for the next rate increase on the 737 (to 21 a month from 14) and
working aggressively to reduce our overall cost structure," the
company said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
