<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation of State Securities Deepens Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The financial crisis in the
Republic of Moldova is made even more worse by a related
phenomenon, inflation of the government securities, National Bank
governor Leonid Talmaci told a recent meeting with businessmen.
</P>
<P>
The state has issued securities in such a great number that the
internal debt represents just two thirds of the monetary mass in
circulation, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
The inflation of securities, he said, is expressed in high
interest. In the first half of this year, the interest rate of the
most sought securities rose from 27 up to 35 percent, while the
inflation in the same period increased just 2.54 percent and the
refinancing rate for credits was between 16 and 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
To convince the public to purchase more securities, the
government raises the interest, said Talmaci.
</P>
<P>
By the end of May the securities market was shaken by first
alarming signals: the reimbursement exceeded the real income from
the new sales. In June the Finance Ministry repaid securities of
144 million lei (30.64 million U.S. dollars), while the revenue
from the new issuances soared to only 98.3 million lei (20.9
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Conceived and presented as an uninflational source of recovery
of the deficit, the government securities have become something
that generates new internal debts. The state spends increasingly
more money to repay the treasury bonds, Deputy Premier and
Economics Minister Ion Sturza told journalists.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the internal debt rose 1.7-fold and the cost of
recovery two-fold. This year the Finance Ministry repaid interests
of 57.5 million lei (12.23 million dollars) to securities holders.
</P>
<P>
The pyramid of securities, built by the government to cover the
budgetary deficit, is now trembling. Some experts think that the
next months the ministry may confront face to face the problem of
securities repayment.
</P>
<P>
Investors with serious business intentions are leaving the
Moldovan market. If a year ago some 50 percent of all treasury
bonds were purchased by foreigners, now they demand only 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
To avoid the collapse of the securities pyramid, the government
is planning to issue more and more securities. Last year the
Finance Ministry sold securities of 1.28 billion lei (272.34
million dollars) plus another package of 773.4 million lei (164.55
dollars) in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Deputy Premier Ion Sturza, these conditions should
make the government cut down the mass of loans on the internal
market and, on the other hand, cut down the interest.
</P>
<P>
Internal loans, he said, are now even more expensive than the
foreign credits. Finance Ministry experts believe that the
interest rate of securities should be reduced unless it fits the
real growth in economics.
</P>
<P>
However, no viable mechanism has been applied so far to
diminish the negative effects of the securities inflation and
their costs are constantly rising. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
