<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street rallied into
the close Wednesday, pushing the Dow Jones industrial average to
its first finish above 9,000 in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Dow jumped 96.65 to 9,048.67 after nearly faltering for the
fifth straight session in a bid to hold above 9,000.
</P>
<P>
The barometer of 30 big companies has risen in six of the past
seven sessions, gaining 337 points, and now sits just 163 points
shy of May 13's record close of 9,211.84. The Dow's last finish
above 9,000 was on June 9.
</P>
<P>
Broad-market indicators also rallied over the final hour after
posting modest gains for most of the day.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 14.72 to 1,148.56, topping
Monday's high of 1,138.49. It closed at a new high for the fourth
time in six sessions.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite rose 19.72 to 1,914.46, just shy of its
all-time best finish of 1,917.61 set on April 22 and the first
close above 1,900 since that record was set. The Nasdaq has surged
nearly 12 percent over the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by more than a 2-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 682.79
million shares, down from 754.85 million on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index up 6.87 to 585.60, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index rose 2.03 to 723.31.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.46 to
459.85.
</P>
<P>
The market opened strong amid news reports saying Japan's
leaders are set to propose sweeping tax cuts to stimulate the
sputtering Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
The reports came as Federal Reserve officials were concluding a
two-day meeting with no change in the central bank's key lending
rates.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo share prices rallied 3.4 percent as a leading Japanese
newspaper reported that Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto plans to
introduce permanent tax cuts of up to 4 trillion yen, or about 29
billion U.S. dollars, next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
