<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Impose New Tough Controls on Arms Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Labor government Wednesday
published a draft legislation, setting out new plans on tightening
controls over arms exports.
</P>
<P>
The draft legislation, presented by British Trade and Industry
Secretary Margaret Beckett, would for the first time give
parliament the right to scrutinize changes to restrictions on
arms exports.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules, any changes to government guidelines on
arms exports will not automatically go before parliament for
approval, but the parliament will be able to examine changes and
pass a resolution if it disagrees with them.
</P>
<P>
The new legislation is also expected to grant the Customs
authorities greater powers to investigate alleged breaches of
British arms embargoes.
</P>
<P>
Beckett said in a statement, "It is important in a modern
democracy for government to be accountable to parliament for the
way it uses its strategic export control powers."
</P>
<P>
Due to the coming summer recess of the parliament, the draft
legislation will not be presented to the parliament until this
autumn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
