<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diana Museum Opens to Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- About 2,500 people visited the last
resting place of Diana, Princess of Wales, as Althorp Park was
opened Wednesday for the first time since her death last August.
</P>
<P>
They came with flowers and cards to pay tribute to Diana on her
birthday and were eager to see her childhood home and resting
place.
</P>
<P>
Althorp House, the Spencer family's rural estate, flung open
its gates to welcome Diana fans and curious onlookers.
</P>
<P>
Visitors had their first glimpse of a new museum built in the
princess's memory and of the island on which she was buried.
</P>
<P>
From the early school reports to moving footage of her funeral,
the museum traced the life of the girl who became a princess and
touched the hearts of millions with her unique blend of glamor,
compassion and love-hate relationship with the media who pursued
her until death.
</P>
<P>
Diana's brother, Earl Charles Spencer, greeted the visitors
with smiles and posed for photographs in the grounds of the house
which cynics have slammed as "Dianaville," but which the first
delighted tourists called tasteful and dignified.
</P>
<P>
More than 150,000 people are expected to visit the
Northamptonshire house over the next two months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
