<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Down Against Yen, Up Against Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell against the
yen Wednesday on continued optimism that Japan is finally ready to
make the steps needed to push up its recessionary economy.
</P>
<P>
The dollar rose against the mark as Russian data released
Wednesday showed its economy is slipping further.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 138.07 yen,
down from 139.16 late Tuesday. The U.S. currency also was changing
hands at 1.8187 marks, up from 1.8080.
</P>
<P>
The latest news came Wednesday, when a Japanese newspaper
reported that the Japanese prime minister will introduce permanent
income and residential tax cuts of up to 29 million U.S. dollars
next year.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, top politicians are to reveal details about a
bridge bank that will help tidy up Japan's overwhelmed banking
system, which is slumping as Japan endures its worst recession
since World War II.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday:
1.5285 Swiss francs, up from 1.5195; 6.0935 French francs, up from
6.0595; 1,791.00 Italian lire, up from 1,776.99; and 1.4615
Canadian dollars, down from 1.4700.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6603 U.S. dollars down from
1.6667 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
