<HEADLINE> Italian FM on NATO's Further Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 1 (Xinhua) -- NATO will persevere in its
open-door policy to all the applicant countries and Italy will
continue to support Romania and Slovenia in their bid to join NATO
quickly, said Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister, who is on a one-day official visit in
Romania, said that NATO's enlargement had to be seen as a process
with no limitations set beforehand. "Italy is interested in a
second wave of NATO enlargement designed to fortify the alliance's
southern flank and wished it to start in 1999," Dini said at a
press conference, together with his Romanian counterpart Andrei
Plesu.
</P>
<P>
The Italian chief diplomat explained that Romania would be of
help in strengthening Europe and NATO, security and stability in
the region. He said that NATO's expansion itself and the date for
its start were uncertain, but "it is clear that Romania and
Slovenia are the prime countries to be admitted, as is stipulated
in the Madrid Declaration."
</P>
<P>
Romanian Foreign Minister Andrei Plesu said that it was too
early now to say something definite about the date of NATO's
further expansion but that it was important for Romania "to be
ready" when the process started.
</P>
<P>
As it was reported here, Italy and France are among the NATO
member countries which consistently supported and supports
Romania's bid to join the Euro-Atlantic structures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
