<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Charges Against Ex-Justice Official Dismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- In a major blow to Whitewater
prosecutors, a federal judge Wednesday dismissed the tax evasion
case against former Justice Department official and presidential
friend Webster Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
U.S. District Judge James Robertson granted a defense request
to dismiss the charges because the case was built on evidence
Hubbell had turned over under a grant of limited immunity from
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
The judge's decision also means that all charges brought by
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr against Hubbell's wife, Suzy,
his accountant and his tax lawyer will be dropped, according to
media reports.
</P>
<P>
Robertson ruled that Starr "built his case against Mr. Hubbell
using 13,120 pages of records that Mr. Hubbell was compelled to
produce under subpoena."
</P>
<P>
The prosecutor's use of the documents "violates the immunity
given to Mr. Hubbell" by a federal judge in Arkansas, the judge
said.
</P>
<P>
Hubbell turned over his personal tax documents to Whitewater
prosecutors under a limited grant of immunity, meaning that Starr
was not to use the material to prosecute Hubbell. The records had
been subpoenaed by the prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
"The subpoena served on Mr. Hubbell was the quintessential
fishing expedition," Robertson said. "The independent counsel
freely admits that he was not investigating tax-related charges
when he issued it."
</P>
<P>
The judge said that by giving the documents to Starr, "Mr.
Hubbell was thereby turned into the primary informant against
himself."
</P>
<P>
Last week, Robertson signaled his displeasure with Starr's
decision to prosecute Hubbell a second time, saying prosecutors
had a "scary" view of the Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
During that hearing, the judge sharply questioned prosecutors
about their handling of the tax evasion indictment against Hubbell
and the three others.
</P>
<P>
Hubbell, a golfing buddy of President Bill Clinton and former
law partner of Hillary Rodham Clinton, has been a key figure in
the four-year Whitewater investigation.
</P>
<P>
A little over a year into Clinton's presidency, Hubbell
resigned as the No. 3 Justice Department official under a cloud of
allegations he had defrauded the former Arkansas law firm where he
and Mrs. Clinton had worked.
</P>
<P>
In December 1994 he pleaded guilty to tax evasion and mail
fraud and promised to cooperate with Starr's investigation of the
Clintons' Arkansas business dealings. He served 19 months.
</P>
<P>
Robertson's decision follows a series of recent setbacks for
Starr. They include the Supreme Court decision that a lawyer for
White House aide Vincent Foster does not have to surrender notes
taken in conversations shortly before Foster killed himself; the
release of Clinton business partner Susan McDougal from prison;
and the Supreme Court's refusal to give emergency consideration to
Starr's attempts to force testimony from three Secret Service
employees and presidential aide Bruce Lindsey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
