<HEADLINE> N.Irish Assembly Elects Trimble First Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's Ulster Unionist
Party leader David Trimble was elected first minister of the
Northern Ireland Assembly at its inaugural meeting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Social Democratic and Labor Party's deputy Seamus Mallon
was elected second minister.
</P>
<P>
"No one at this stage can say with absolute certainty that
success is guaranteed," Trimble said after the election. But he
added, "We have started on the long march towards a better future
and we are determined to continue."
</P>
<P>
His deputy Mallon said, "We share hope. We share a conviction
that now, at the end of this century, we are going to change the
face of life in the north of Ireland."
</P>
<P>
"I feel a great sense of humility -- and it's not a virtue that
I am normally imbued with," he added.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's first assembly meeting marked a milestone in its
long and troubled peace process as those who killed each other to
end or prolong British rule gathered side by side with victims of
their "war" and their arch-enemies as key players in a new
assembly.
</P>
<P>
But the assembly has a long way to achieve peace in the
province. Trimble faces a mammoth task of trying to heal a wound
in the Protestant community which has festered since it became
clear Sinn Fein would for the first time work in a body under
British jurisdiction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
